# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bachelor-of-science
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] An **academic certificate** or **tech certificate** is a document that certifies that a person has received specific education or has passed a test or series of tests.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] In many countries, a certificate is a qualification attained in secondary education.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] For instance, students in Ireland sit the Junior Certificate and follow it with the Leaving Certificate.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] Similarly, other countries have awards, for instance, in Australia the Higher School Certificate (HSC) in New South Wales, the Victorian Certificate of Education (VCE) in Victoria, etc., is the examination taken on completion of secondary education.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] In parts of the United Kingdom the General Certificate of Secondary Education (GCSE) is the normal examination taken at age 16 and the General Certificate of Education (GCE) Advanced Subsidiary Level (AS-level) and Advanced Level (A-levels) are taken at 17 and 18.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] In many other countries, certificates are qualifications in higher education.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] For example, the National Certificate in Ireland, which was replaced in 2006 by the "Higher Certificate".
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] These have the titles Certificate (at an undergraduate level), Graduate Certificate (at an undergraduate level, but requiring the completion of a prior undergraduate degree for admission), and Postgraduate Certificate (at a postgraduate level).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] In Hong Kong, students take the exams to receive Hong Kong Diploma of Secondary Education.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] Certificate is below the standard of the associate degree, diploma, higher diploma and advanced diploma, which are below the bachelor's degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] Postgraduate certificates are taken after the bachelor's degree and are sometimes more vocationally oriented than master's degrees.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] In Australia, a certificate is a qualification offered by a university or other higher education provider which is shorter than a degree or diploma.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] Certificates are generally provided by TAFE colleges or non-academic registered training organizations (often workplaces).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] There are four ranks of certificate in Australia, indicated by Roman numerals, e.g., Cert.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] The time spent varies, but in general a Certificate I will be granted after a course of only a few weeks, while a Cert.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] IV and may rightly be considered equivalent to a hypothetical Certificate V.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] In the United Kingdom, a Certificate of Higher Education (CertHE) requires successful completion of 120 credits at level four of the Framework for Higher Education Qualifications (level 7 of the Scottish Credit and Qualifications Framework).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] This is equivalent to one year of full-time university education at first-year level.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] Each credit is equivalent to a nominal ten hours of study, and as such the CertHE is 1,200 hours of study.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] This compares with 360 credits (spanning levels 4, 5 and 6/480 credits spanning levels 7 to 10 in Scotland) for an honours bachelor's degree, and 240 credits (spanning level 4 and 5/7 and 8 in Scotland) for a Diploma of Higher Education.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] A certificate can also be a vocational qualification of between 13 and 36 credits at any of the levels of the Regulated Qualifications Framework, the level being specified in the qualification title.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] In the United States, a certificate may be offered by an institute of higher education.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] These certificates usually signify that a student has reached a standard of knowledge about a certain vocational or professional subject.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] Certificate programs can be completed more quickly than associate degrees and often do not have general education requirements.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] Undergraduate certificates represent completion of a specific program offered in coordination with a bachelor's degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] Graduate certificates represent completion of studies beyond the bachelor's degree, yet short of a master's degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] It also may be awarded as a necessary certification to validate that a student is considered competent in a certain specific networking skill area in information technology.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] It is becoming more common for higher education institutions to award certificates to continuing education students.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] These certificates vary, usually involve rigorous courses, and can be affiliated with many associations.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] University certificates are also becoming more common ways for people to engage in areas of interest while working full-time.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] They can be completed with a minimum grade in a series of university courses, and are sometimes taken as a way to further one's professional career (either by requirement or choice).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-certificate] They are gaining credence and ground in both the academic world and the working world.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] An **academic degree** is a qualification awarded to a student upon successful completion of a course of study in higher education.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Academic degrees are commonly structured in levels, most often categorized as undergraduate and postgraduate degrees.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] The most common undergraduate qualification is the bachelor's degree, although some educational systems also offer lower-level degrees such as the associate degree or the foundation degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Postgraduate degrees include the engineer's degree, the master's degree, and the doctorate.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] In the UK and countries whose educational systems are based on the British system, honours degrees are divided into classes: first, second (broken into upper second, or 2.1, and lower second, or 2.2) and third class.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] The doctorate (Latin: *doceo*, "I teach") first appeared in medieval Europe as a license to teach (Latin: *licentia docendi*) at a medieval university.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Its roots can be traced to the early church when the term "doctor" referred to the Apostles, Church Fathers and other Christian authorities who taught and interpreted the Bible.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] The right to grant a *licentia docendi* was originally reserved by the church which required the applicant to pass a test, take an oath of allegiance, and pay a fee.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] The Third Council of the Lateran of 1179 guaranteed the access – now largely free of charge – of all able applicants, who were, however, still tested for aptitude by the ecclesiastic scholastic.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] This right remained a point of contention between the church authorities and the slowly emancipating universities, but was granted by the Pope to the University of Paris in 1231 where it became a universal license to teach (*licentia ubique docendi*).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] While the *licentia* continued to hold a higher prestige than the bachelor's degree (*Baccalaureus*), it was ultimately reduced to an intermediate step to the Magister and doctorate, both of which now became the exclusive qualification for teaching.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] In universities, doctoral training was a form of apprenticeship to a guild.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] The traditional term of study before new teachers were admitted to the guild of "Master of Arts" was seven years.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] This was the same as the term of apprenticeship for other occupations.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Originally the terms "master" and "doctor" were synonymous, but over time the doctorate came to be regarded as a higher qualification than the master's degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Today the terms "master" (from the Latin *magister*, lit.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] 'teacher'), "Doctor", and "Professor" signify different levels of academic achievement, but in the Medieval university, they were equivalent terms.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] The use of them in the degree name was a matter of custom at a university.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Most universities conferred the Master of Arts, although the highest degree was often termed Master of Theology/Divinity or Doctor of Theology/Divinity, depending on the place.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] The earliest doctoral degrees (theology – *Divinitatis* Doctor (D.D.), law – *Legum* Doctor (LL.D., later D.C.L.) and medicine – *Medicinæ* Doctor (M.D., D.M.)) reflected the historical separation of all higher university study into these three fields.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Over time, the D.D. has gradually become less common outside theology and is now mostly used for honorary degrees, with the title "Doctor of Theology" being used more often for earned degrees.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Studies outside theology, law, and medicine were then called "philosophy", due to the Renaissance conviction that real knowledge could be derived from empirical observation.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] The degree title of Doctor of Philosophy is a much later creation and was not introduced in England before 1900.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Studies in what once was called philosophy are now classified as sciences and humanities.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] George Makdisi theorizes that the *ijazah* issued in medieval Islamic madrasas in the 9th century was the origin of the doctorate that later appeared in medieval European universities.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Alfred Guillaume, Syed Farid al-Attas and Devin J.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Stewart agree that there is a resemblance between the *ijazah* and the university degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] However, Toby Huff and others reject Makdisi's theory.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Stewart finds that the *ijazat al-ifta*, license to teach Islamic law and issue legal opinions, is most similar to the medieval European university degree in that it permits entry into certain professions.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] A key difference was that the granting authority of the *ijaza* was an individual professor whereas the university degree was granted by a corporate entity.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] The University of Bologna in Italy, regarded as the oldest university in Europe, was the first institution to confer the degree of Doctor in Civil Law in the late 12th century; it also conferred similar degrees in other subjects, including medicine.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] The University of Paris used the term "master" for its graduates, a practice adopted by the English universities of Oxford and Cambridge, as well as the ancient Scottish universities of St Andrews, Glasgow, Aberdeen and Edinburgh.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] The term "bachelor" comes from the Latin *baccalaureus*, a term previously used to describe a squire (i.e., apprentice) to a knight.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Further study and, in particular, successful participation in, and moderation of, disputations would earn one the Master of Arts degree, from the Latin magister, "master" (typically indicating a teacher), entitling one to teach these subjects.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Masters of Arts were eligible to enter study under the "higher faculties" of Law, Medicine or Theology and earn first a bachelor's and then master's or doctor's degree in these subjects.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Thus, a degree was only a step on the way to becoming a fully qualified master – hence the English word "graduate", which is based on the Latin *gradus* ("step").
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] The naming of degrees eventually became linked to the subjects studied.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Scholars in the faculties of arts or grammar became known as "masters", but those in theology, medicine and law were known as "doctors".
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] As a study in the arts or grammar was a necessary prerequisite to study in subjects such as theology, medicine and law, the degree of doctor assumed a higher status than the master's degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] This led to the modern hierarchy in which the Doctor of Philosophy (Ph.D.), which in its present form as a degree based on research and dissertation is a development from 18th- and 19th-century German universities, is a more advanced degree than the Master of Arts (M.A.).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] The practice of using the term *doctor* for PhDs developed within German universities and spread across the academic world.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] The French terminology is tied closely to the original meanings of the terms.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] "bachelor") is conferred upon French students who have completed their secondary education and allows the student to attend university.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] When students graduate from university, they are awarded a *licence*, much as the medieval teaching guilds would have done, and they are qualified to teach in secondary schools or proceed to higher-level studies.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Spain had a similar structure: the term *"Bachiller"* was used for those who finished the secondary or high-school level education, known as *"Bachillerato"*.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] The standard Spanish university 5-year degree was *"Licenciado"*, (although there were a few 3-year associate degrees called *"diplomaturas"*, from where the *"diplomados"* could move to study a related *licenciatura*).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] In the past, degrees have been directly issued by the authority of the monarch or by a bishop, rather than any educational institution.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] In Great Britain, Lambeth degrees are still awarded by the Archbishop of Canterbury.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] The Archbishop of Canterbury's right to grant degrees is derived from the Peter's Pence Act 1533, which empowered the Archbishop to grant dispensations previously granted by the Pope.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Among educational institutions, St David's College, Lampeter, was granted limited degree awarding powers by royal charter in the nineteenth century, despite not being a university.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] The University College of North Staffordshire was also granted degree awarding powers on its foundation in 1949, despite not becoming a university (as the University of Keele) until 1962.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Following the Education Reform Act 1988, many educational institutions other than universities have been granted degree-awarding powers, including higher education colleges and colleges of the University of London, many of which are now effectively universities in their own right.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] In many countries, gaining an academic degree entitles the holder to assume distinctive academic dress particular to the awarding institution, identifying the status of the individual wearing them.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] In many countries, degrees may only be awarded by institutions authorised to do so by the national or regional government.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Frequently, governments will also regulate the use of the word *university* in the names of businesses.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] This approach is followed, for example, by Australia, the United Kingdom and Israel.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] The use of fake degrees by individuals, either obtained from a bogus institution or simply invented, is often covered by fraud laws.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Depending on the culture and the degree earned, degrees may be indicated by a pre-nominal title, post-nominal letters, a choice of either, or not indicated at all.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] In countries influenced by the UK, post-nominal letters are the norm, with only doctorates granting a title, while titles are the norm in many northern European countries.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Depending on the culture and the purpose of the listing, only the highest degree, a selection of degrees, or all degrees might be listed.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] The awarding institution may be shown and it might be specified if a degree was at honours level, particularly where the honours degree is a separate qualification from the ordinary bachelor's degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] For member institutions of the Association of Commonwealth Universities, there is a standard list of abbreviations for university names given in the Commonwealth Universities Yearbook.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] In practice, many variations are used and the Yearbook notes that the abbreviations used may not match those used by the universities concerned.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Other Latin abbreviations commonly used include 'Cantuar' for Lambeth degrees (awarded by the Archbishop of Canterbury), 'Dunelm' for Durham University, 'Ebor' for the University of York and 'Exon' for the University of Exeter.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] The Ancient universities of Scotland and the University of London have abbreviations that are the same in English and Latin.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Confusion can result from universities sharing similar names, e.g. the University of York in the UK and York University in Canada or Newcastle University in the UK and the University of Newcastle in Australia.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] In this case, the convention is to include a country abbreviation with the university's name.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] For example, 'York (Can.)' and 'York (UK)' or 'Newc (UK)' and 'Newc (Aus.) are commonly used to denote degrees conferred by these universities where the potential for confusion exists, and institution names are given in this form in the Commonwealth Universities Yearbook.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Abbreviations used for degrees vary between countries and institutions, e.g.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] MS indicates Master of Science in the US and places following American usage, but Master of Surgery in the UK and most Commonwealth countries, where the standard abbreviation for Master of Science is MSc.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Common abbreviations include BA and MA for Bachelor and Master of Arts, BS/BSc and MS/MSc for Bachelor and Master of Science, MD for Doctor of Medicine and PhD for Doctor of Philosophy.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p01] Improvements in technology, the increasing use of the Internet worldwide, and the need for people to have flexible school schedules that enable them to work while attending school have led to a proliferation of online colleges that award associate's, bachelor's, master's, and doctoral degrees.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Bangladesh and India mostly follow the colonial era British system for the classification of degrees, however, Pakistan has recently switched to the US model of a two-year associate degree and a four-year bachelor's degree program.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The arts, referring to the performing arts and literature, may confer a Bachelor of Arts (BA) and a Master of Arts (MA).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Management degrees are also classified under 'arts' but are nowadays considered a separate stream, with degrees of Bachelor of Business Administration (BBA) and Master of Business Administration (MBA).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Science refers to the basic sciences and natural science (Biology, Physics, Chemistry, etc.); the corresponding degrees are Bachelor of Science (BSc) and Master of Science (MSc).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Information Technology degrees are conferred specially in the field of computer science, and include Bachelor of Science in Information Technology (B.Sc.IT.) and Master of Science in Information Technology (M.Sc.IT.).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The engineering degree in India follows two nomenclatures, Bachelor of Engineering (B.Eng.) and Bachelor of Technology (B.Tech.).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Both represent bachelor's degree in engineering.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] In Pakistan, engineering degrees are Bachelor of Engineering (B.E.) and Bachelor of Science in Engineering (B.S./B.Sc.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Both are the same in curriculum, duration and pattern, and differ only in nomenclature.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The engineering degree in Bangladesh is a Bachelor of Science in Engineering (B.Sc.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Indonesia follows a higher education system that originated from the Dutch colonial period.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] However, over the years, Indonesia has transitioned from the Dutch degree classification system and developed its own academic distinctions by translating and adapting its degree structure.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] All degrees in Indonesia follow standardized regulations.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The duration of each program is specified by Regulation of the Minister of Education and Culture of the Republic of Indonesia Number 3 of 2020 on National Standards of Higher Education.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The regulation outlines the maximum duration and minimum credit requirements (Semester Credit Units or SKS) for each level of study without counting academic leave.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The degree structure follows a standardized pattern, where XX represents the specific field of study.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Since a semester consists of 14 or 15 weeks of coursework and 1 or 2 weeks of exams, one SKS translates to an average of 40 hours of study per semester.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Comparatively, one European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System (ECTS) credit equals 28 hours of study, meaning that one Indonesian SKS is approximately equivalent to 1.5 ECTS.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Therefore, a bachelor's degree in Indonesia (minimum 144 SKS) is roughly equivalent to 216 ECTS, which surpasses the standard European requirement of 180 ECTS for a bachelor's degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] All degrees in Indonesia grant academic titles, which are often used in formal and social settings, including on unofficial documents such as marriage invitations.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Before Indonesia adopted its modern degree classification, the country used a system copied from the Dutch colonial academic structure, which in Netherlands remained extant to 2002.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] In this system, university students typically studied for five years before graduating.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] This structure was different from the modern four-year bachelor's (S1) degree, as it allowed graduates to proceed directly to a doctorate (S3) program without first obtaining a master's (S2) degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] This system included pre-nominal academic titles that have largely been phased out but are still recognized, for those who graduated before 1992.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Some of these titles are still in limited use today.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Doktorandus (Drs.) and Doktoranda (Dra.) originated from Latin, meaning "one who is to become a doctor." These titles indicated that the degree holder only needed to complete a dissertation to obtain a doctorate.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Until the 1960s, diplomas from Bandung Institute of Technology (ITB) explicitly stated that holders were entitled to pursue a doctorate upon defending a thesis.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] After the 1970s, ITB replaced Doktorandus and Insinyur (Engineer) titles with Sarjana (Bachelor) degrees.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] However, these titles remained granted and used until 1992 in other universities or institutes.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] By aligning with Anglo education standards, Indonesia transitioned to the B.Sc. - M.Sc. - Ph.D. model, similar to the Bologna Process.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Unlike the previous system, where five-year graduates could proceed directly to a Ph.D., students must now complete an S1 (Bachelor's) and S2 (Master's) before pursuing S3 (Doctorate).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Despite this transition, many pre-1992 graduates retained the use of their original titles granted upon their graduation, making formats such as Prof.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Drs. [Name] common among senior academics and professionals.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Sri Lanka, like many other commonwealth countries, follows the British system, but with its own distinctions.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Degrees are approved by the University Grants Commission.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Tunisia's educational grading system, ranging from elementary school to Ph.D. programs, operates on a scale of 0 to 20.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The minimum score for passing is set at 10 out of 20.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] This numerical system exclusively evaluates a student's academic accomplishments, serving as the determinant for admission into advanced programs.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] For instance, a student's grades obtained for their bachelor's degree are considered when they apply for a Master's program.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Level 4 courses, which include the first year of a Bachelor's program or a Higher National Certificate (HNC), may allow students to enter directly into the second year of a Bachelor's program, provided that the course they completed is the same as the one they are applying for.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] In South Africa, grades (also known as "marks") are presented as a percentage, with anything below 50% considered a failure.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Students who receive a failing grade may have the opportunity to rewrite the exam, depending on the criteria established by their institution.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Degrees in almost any field of study can be pursued at one of the institutions in the country, with certain institutions being known for excelling in specific fields.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Major fields of study across the country include Arts, Commerce, Engineering, Law, Medicine, Science, and Theology.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The South African Qualifications Authority (SAQA) has developed a credit-based system for degrees, with different levels of National Qualifications Framework (NQF) ratings corresponding to each degree level.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] For example, an undergraduate degree in Science is rated at NQF level 6, while an additional year of study in that discipline would result in an NQF level 8 (honours degree) rating.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] In Kenya, the first undergraduate degree is pursued after students have completed four years of secondary school education and attained at least a C+ (55–59%) on the Kenya Certificate of Secondary Education (KCSE).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Students pursuing a degree in engineering, such as B.Sc.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Electrical and Electronics Engineering, are required to join programs that are accredited by the Engineers Board of Kenya and the Commission for University Education.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The B.Sc. degree in engineering typically takes five years to complete.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] A degree in medicine or surgery may take six to seven years, while a degree in education or management takes around four years.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] For students pursuing a master's degree, they must have completed an undergraduate degree and attained at least a second-class honours upper division (60–69%) or lower division plus at least two years of relevant experience.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Most master's degree programs take two years to complete.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] In an engineering master's degree program, students are typically required to publish at least one scientific paper in a peer-reviewed journal.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] To pursue a doctor of philosophy degree, students must have completed a relevant master's degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] They are required to carry out a supervised scientific study for a minimum of three years and publish at least two scientific first-author papers in peer-reviewed journals relevant to their area of study.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Currently, Kenya is implementing a Competency Based Curriculum (CBC) that follows a 2–6–3–3 education system to replace the existing 8–4–4 system which allows confirmation of undergraduate degrees upon successful completion.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] This system is gradually replacing the two-stage system previously used in some countries and is combined with other elements such as the European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System (ECTS) and the use of Diploma Supplements to make comparisons between qualifications easier.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The European Higher Education Area (EHEA) was formally established in 2010 and, as of September 2016, has 50 members.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The implementation of the various elements of the EHEA varies between countries.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Twenty-four countries have fully implemented a national qualifications framework, and a further ten have a framework but have not yet certified it against the overarching framework.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] In 38 countries, ECTS credits are used for all higher education programmes, and 31 countries have fully implemented diploma supplements.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Only 11 countries have included all the major points of the Lisbon Recognition Convention in national legislation.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Since 2008, the European Union has been developing the European Qualifications Framework (EQF).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] This is an eight-level framework designed to allow cross-referencing of the various national qualifications frameworks.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] While it is not specific to higher education, the top four levels (5–8) correspond to the short cycle, first cycle, second cycle, and third cycle of the EHEA.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The two-cycle degree system was phased out by 2010, with a few exceptions.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] However, some of the established degree naming has been preserved, allowing universities to award the "Diplom-Ingenieur" (and for a while also the "Magister") to graduates of the new-style Master programmes.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] While higher education is regulated by the three communities of Belgium, all have common and comparable systems of degrees that were adapted to the Bologna structure during the 2000s.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The primary 3-cycle structure is called BMD (Bachelor-Master-Doctorate; French: *Bachelier-Master-Doctorat* or Dutch: *Bachelor-Master-Doctoraat*).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] In the first cycle, the Bachelor's degree is issued after 180 ECTS (3 years, EQF level 6).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Other first cycle degrees include the one-year Advanced Bachelor's degree degree (French: *Bachelier de spécialisation*, lit.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] 'Specialized Bachelor'; Dutch: *Bachelor-na-bachelor*, lit.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] 'Bachelor-after-bachelor') and the Brevet (in the French-speaking Community only) for short-cycle higher education programmes.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Bachelor's degrees are followed in the second cycle (EQF level 7) by Master's degrees that last two years, completing an extra 120 ECTS credits.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The master's degree can be followed by an Advanced Master's degree (French: *Master de spécialisation*, lit.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] 'Specialized Master'; Dutch: *Master-na-master*, lit.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] 'Master-after-master') that lasts one year (60 ECTS).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The Czech Republic has implemented the Bologna process, and functionally has three degrees: Bachelor (3 years), Master (2 years after Bachelor) and Doctor (4 years after Master).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The Czech Republic also has voluntary academic titles called "small doctorates" (e.g.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] RNDr. for natural sciences, PhDr. for philosophy, JUDr. for law etc.) which are achieved after passing an additional exam.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Medical students do not get bachelor's or master's degrees, but instead attend a six-year program and obligatory exam they achieve the title MUDr.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] (equivalent to MD degree in the United States of America), or MDDr. for dentists and MVDr. for veterinary physicians.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] They can also get a "big doctorate" (Ph.D.) after another three or four years of study.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Bachelor's degrees, master's degrees and small doctorates in the form of letters (Bc., Mgr., Ing., ...) are listed before the person's name, and Doctor's degrees (Ph.D.) are listed after name (e.g.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The Czech Republic previously had more degrees that were awarded.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Before the adoption of the Bologna Process, the lowest degree that would normally be studied at universities in Denmark was equivalent to a master's degree (*kandidatgrad*).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Officially, a bachelor's degree was always obtained after 3 years' university studies.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Various medium-length (2–4 years) professional degrees have been adopted, so they now have status as professional bachelor's degrees of varying length.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] As opposed to academic bachelor's degrees, they are considered to be "applied" degrees.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] A professional bachelor's degree is 180, 210, or 240 ECTS-points.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Historically, the Finnish higher education system is derived from the German system.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The current system of higher education comprises two types of higher education institutions, the universities and the polytechnics, many of whom refer to themselves as universities of applied sciences (UAS).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] With the exception of a few fields, such as medicine and dentistry, the Finnish system of higher education degrees is in compliance with the Bologna process.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Universities award bachelor's degrees (*kandidaatti / kandidat*), Master's degrees (*maisteri / magister*) and doctoral degrees (*lisensiaatin tutkinto / licentiat examen* and *tohtorin tutkinto / doktorexamen*).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] In most fields, the system of doctoral degrees is two-tier, the degree of licentiate is an independent academic degree but completing the degree of doctor does not require completion of a licentiate degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The polytechnics (universities of applied sciences) have the right to award bachelor's and master's degrees; the degree titles are distinct from the titles used for university degrees.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] In general, students who are admitted to bachelor studies at a university have the right to continue to studies at master level.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] At polytechnics, the right to continue to master-level studies has to be applied for separately and there is also a work experience requirement.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The majority of master's degree holders have graduated from university.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The degrees awarded by the universities and polytechnics are at par by law, but the content and orientation of studies is different.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] A master's degree obtained at a polytechnic gives the same academic right to continue studies at doctoral level as a master's degree obtained at a university.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The French national education system makes a distinction between a *diplôme national* ("national degree") and *diplôme universitaire* ("university degree").
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The former, which are considered to have a higher status, are controlled by the state and issued by universities on behalf of the responsible ministry; the latter are controlled and granted by the universities themselves.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Additionally, private universities and schools may be recognised by the state with a *diplôme visé* ("recognised degree") and then, after five years of recognition, have their degrees validated by the state, the validation having to be renewed every six years.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Historically, academic degrees were orientated towards research, and the vocational education system awarded only diplomas.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Since the implementation of the Bologna Process in France, the degree-granting system is being simplified: schools continue to grant their own diplomas, but the state's recognition in degree awarding is more important than before.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] However, in France there are diplomas that are not recognised as degrees, such as specific diplomas designed by colleges (*écoles supérieures*), like the *mastère spécialisé* (accredited by the *Conférence des Grandes Écoles* but not automatically by the French Government).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Since 2002, *grande école* diplomas have been able to award a university degree, such as the Sciences Po *Bachelor*, which is a state-accredited diploma that awards a bachelor's degree (*Licence* in French).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] The recognised degrees are in three levels, following the Qualifications Framework of the European Higher Education Area.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] These are the *licence* (first level), *master* (second level) and *doctorat* (third level).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] All licence degrees take 3 years (180 ECTS credits) and all master's degrees take 2 years (120 ECTS credits).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] There are also 5-year (300 ECTS credits) engineer's degrees, which are master's degrees.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] In addition to the doctorate, which is always a research degree, the *Diplôme d'Etat de docteur en médicine* and the *Diplôme d'Etat de docteur vétérinaire* are third level qualifications and recognized as level 7 in EQF.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] Traditionally in Germany, students studied for four to six years and then graduated with either a *Magister* degree (usually in subjects like humanities, linguistics or the arts) or a *Diplom* degree (typically in fields such as natural sciences, economics, or engineering).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p02] These qualifications were usually the first and highest academic degrees students earned before a doctorate.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Both Magister and Diplom degrees from universities required a final thesis and are generally considered equivalent to a modern master’s degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] However, the Diplom awarded by a *Fachhochschule* (university of applied sciences) is usually considered comparable to a bachelor’s degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] A different type of qualification in Germany is the *Staatsexamen* (state examination).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] This is not an academic degree but a government licensing examination required for certain professions, such as doctors, teachers, lawyers, judges, and pharmacists.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Students typically study at university for three to six years before taking the first Staatsexamen, depending on their field.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] After passing the first Staatsexamen, candidates in fields like law and teaching must complete a practical training period called the *Vorbereitungsdienst* (preparatory service), which usually lasts about two years.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] They then take a second Staatsexamen, which tests their practical skills.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] In some cases, students of law or pharmacy can choose to graduate with a master’s degree instead of taking the first Staatsexamen.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Since 1999, Germany has replaced its traditional university degrees with bachelor’s and master’s degrees as part of the Bologna process.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] This reform aimed to make degrees more comparable internationally and to shorten the overall time students spend in higher education, as older programs often took five years or more to complete.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Today, students typically complete a bachelor’s degree followed by a master’s degree; the first usually taking 3 years, and the latter taking 18 months to 2 years.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Some universities resisted the change, but by the end of 2007 all institutions were required to adopt the new system.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Degree programs that lead to a Staatsexamen (state examination), such as those in law or medicine, were generally not converted to the bachelor’s/master’s system.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] In Germany, doctoral degrees are awarded with different titles depending on the subject area.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Examples include Doktor der Naturwissenschaften (Doctor of Natural Sciences), Doktor der Rechtswissenschaften (Doctor of Law), Doktor der Medizin (Doctor of Medicine), and Doktor der Philosophie (Doctor of Philosophy).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] In German-speaking countries, it is common for people to list multiple doctorates and honorary titles, and sometimes even use them in formal address.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Students who have completed a Diplom, Magister, master’s degree, or Staatsexamen can usually continue on to a doctorate.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] In some cases, particularly strong bachelor’s graduates may also be admitted directly to a doctoral program after passing an aptitude assessment set by the university.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Doctoral degrees (such as Dr. rer. nat. or Dr. phil.) are the highest academic qualifications in Germany and are typically based on independent research.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] (Doctor of Medicine): medical doctors often complete their doctoral thesis shortly after finishing their studies, and it may involve less independent research compared to doctorates in other fields.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Unlike some countries such as the United Kingdom, Germany does not have a system of “higher doctorates” (such as the Doctor of Science).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The Habilitation is an additional qualification beyond the doctorate, although it is not an academic degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] It demonstrates the ability to carry out advanced research and teach at the university level.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] To obtain a Habilitation, candidates usually write a second thesis (called a *Habilitationsschrift*) or submit a collection of significant research publications.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Once completed, the qualification is sometimes abbreviated as “habil.” after a person’s name.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Traditionally, the Habilitation was required to become a *Privatdozent* (a university lecturer qualified to teach independently) and to pursue a professorship.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Today, universities no longer require it, although it can still be an advantage in more traditional academic fields.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] In Greece access to university is possible after national exams (Panhellenic Exams).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Ireland operates under a National Framework of Qualifications (NFQ).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The school-leaving qualification attained by students is called the Leaving Certificate.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] It is considered as Level 4–5 in the framework.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] This qualification is the traditional route of entry into third-level education.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] There are also Level 5 qualifications in certain vocational subjects (e.g.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Level 5 Certificate in Restaurant Operations) awarded by the Further Education and Training Awards Council (FETAC).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Advanced Certificates at Level 6 are also awarded by FETAC.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] These are completed in institutes of technology or universities.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] In Italy access to university is possible after gaining the *Diploma di Maturità* at 19 years of age, following 5 years of study in a specific high school focused on certain subjects (e.g.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] After gaining the diploma one can enter university and enrol in any curriculum (e.g. physics, medicine, chemistry, engineering, architecture): all high school diplomas allow access to any university curriculum, although most universities have pre-admission tests.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] In addition to academic degrees, many professional qualifications are tied to the QTI at the different levels.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The first level, tied to the first cycle of the Bologna Process, covers the *laurea* (bachelor's degree) in universities and the *Diploma accademico di primo livello* in AFAM institutions.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The *laurea* is obtained after three years of study (180 ECTS credits) and confers the academic title of *dottore*; the older university qualifications at this level took two to three years, with the three-year courses conferring the title of *dottore*.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The second level, tied to the second cycle of the Bologna Process, covers the *laurea magistrale* and the *laurea specialistica* of university institutions, and the *Diploma accademico di secondo livello* of AFAM institutions.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The old *Diploma di laurea* is mapped to this level.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The *Laurea magistrale* and the *laurea specialistica* are obtained after two further years of study (120 ECTS credits) and give the academic title of *dottore magistrale*.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The old *Diploma di laurea* took four to six years but was accessed directly from school, with a possible reduction by one year for those with a related *diploma* and also granted the title of *dottore magistrale*.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The third level, tied to the third cycle of the Bologna Process, covers the *Dottorato di ricerca* from university institutions and the *Diploma accademico di formazione alla ricerca* from AFAM institutions.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The old *Dottorato di ricerca* and *Diploma di specializzazione* are tied to this level.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The *Dottorato di ricerca*, under both new and old systems, takes a minimum of three years after the *laurea magistralie/specialistica*, and gives the academic titles of *Dottore di Ricerca (Dott.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The old *Diploma di specializzazione* took two to six years and gave the academic title of *Specialista*.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The *Diploma di specializzazione*, which is offered in a few specific professions, takes two to six years and gives the title of *specialista*.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The *Diploma di perfezionamento* is a university certificate, aimed at professional training or in specific fields of study, which usually takes one year; it is not allocated a level in the framework.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] AFAM institutions may offer the *Diploma di perfezionamento o Master* and *Diploma accademico di specializzazione*.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] These are one-year and two-year qualifications, respectively, and may be offered at the second cycle or third cycle level, distinguished by adding *(I)* or *(II)* after the qualification name.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Higher schools for language mediators offer the *Diploma di mediatore linguistico*, a first-cycle degree that takes three years (180 ECTS credits), and which gives access to the *laurea specialistica*.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Specialisation institutes/schools in psychotherapy offer the *Diploma di specializzazione in psicoterapia*, a third-cycle qualification that takes at least four years and requires a *laurea magistrale/specialistica* in either psychology or medicine and surgery, along with professional registration.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] In the Netherlands, the structure of academic studies was altered significantly in 1982 when the "Tweefasenstructuur" (Two Phase Structure) was introduced by the Dutch Minister of Education, Wim Deetman.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] With this structure an attempt was made to standardise all the different studies and to have them conform to similar timetables.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] An additional effect was that students would be forced to produce results within a preset time-frame or otherwise discontinue their studies.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The two-phase structure has been adapted to a bachelor-master structure as a result of the Bologna process.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] In order for a Dutch student to get access to a university education, the student must complete a six-year pre-university secondary education called *voorbereidend wetenschappelijk onderwijs* (VWO).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] There are other routes possible, but only if the educational level of the applicant is comparable to that at the end of the standard two levels is access to university education granted.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] For some studies, specific end levels or disciplines are required, e.g., graduating without having studied physics, biology and chemistry will make it impossible to study medicine.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] People 21 years old, or older, who do not have the required entrance diplomas, may opt for an entrance exam to be admitted to a higher-educational curriculum.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] In this exam, they have to prove their command of disciplines considered necessary for pursuing such study.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] After 1 September 2002, they would be thus admitted to a Bachelor's curriculum, not to a Master's curriculum.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] For some disciplines in the Netherlands, a governmentally determined limited access is in place (although under political review for abolishment, as of February 2011).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] This limits the number of applicants to a specific course of study, thus trying to control the number of future graduates.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The disciplines most renowned for their numerus clausus are medicine and dentistry.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Every year a combination of the highest pre-university graduation grades and some additional conditions determine who can start such a numerus clausus course of study and who can not.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Almost all Dutch universities are government supported, with only a few privately owned universities in existence (i.e. one in business and all others in theology).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Leiden University is the oldest, founded in 1575.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] For medical students the "doctorandus" degree is not equivalent to the European Anglo Saxon postgraduate research degree in medicine, of MD (Medical Doctor).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Besides the title doctorandus, the graduates of the Curius curriculum may also bear the title *arts* (physician).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The doctorandus in medicine title is granted after four years (nominal time) of the Curius curriculum, while the title physician is granted after six years (nominal time) of that curriculum.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The Dutch physician title is equal to a MSc degree according to the Bologna process and can be compared with the MBBS in the UK degree system and the North American MD, but not the UK MD degree, which is a research degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] One-on-one equivalence or interchangeability of the Dutch medical title and MD is often suggested.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] However, officially the MD title is not known, nor legal to use, in the Netherlands.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The correct notation for a Dutch physician who completed his or her medical studies, but did not pursue a doctoral (PhD-like) study is "drs." (e.g.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Jansen, arts*) and not "dr." in medicine, which is often used incorrectly.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] However, like in the United Kingdom, physicians holding these degrees are referred to as 'Doctor' by courtesy.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] In the Netherlands, there is the informal title *dokter* for physicians, but not *doctor* (dr.), unless they also earn such adegree by completing a PhD curriculum.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Furthermore, the *doctorandus* degree does not give a medical student the right to treat patients; for this a minimum of two years of additional study (internship) is required.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] After obtaining a Medical Board registration, Dutch physicians must work an additional two to six years in a field of expertise to become a registered medical specialist.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Dutch surgeons commonly are only granted access to surgical training and positions after obtaining a doctorate (PhD) successfully.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] In recent years, the six-year (nominal time) old Curius curriculum (which offered the titles doctorandus and physician) has been replaced with a three-year (nominal time) Bachelor Curius+ followed by a three-year (nominal time) Master Curius+.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Those who had already begun their old-style Curius curriculum before that will still have to complete it as a six-year study (nominal time).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] A doctorandus in law uses the title *meester* (master, abbreviated as *mr.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Jansen*) instead of drs., and some courses of study, such as in technology and agriculture< grant the title *ingenieur* (engineer, noted as *ir.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] These titles as equivalent to an LL.M (the title "mr.") and to a MSc (the title "ir.") and if gotten before 1 September 2002, from a recognized Dutch university, may be rendered as M (from Master) behind one's name, instead of using the typical Dutch honorifics before one's name.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] However, this M is hardly used in favor of the typical Dutch titles ("drs.", "ir.", "mr."), or MSc, MA or LLM.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Since 1 September 2002, Dutch universities offer specific BSc, BA or LLB studies followed by MSc, MA or LLM studies, thus integrating into the international scientific community, offering lectures, other classes, seminars or complete curricula in English instead of Dutch.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] According to their field of study, MSc graduates may use either ir. or drs. before their names; MA graduates may use drs. before their name; LLM graduates may use mr. before their names, but only if they received such degrees from recognized Dutch universities.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Not uncommonly, the Dutch "drs." abbreviation can cause much confusion in other countries, since it is perceived as a person who has a PhD in multiple disciplines.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] In the Netherlands, the degree MPhil was not awarded after 2009 as the Universiteiten van Nederland refused to recognize the MPhils awarded by Leiden University.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] After successfully obtaining a "drs.", "ir." or "mr." degree, a student has the opportunity to follow a further, promotional course of study (informally called PhD) to eventually obtain a doctorate and subsequently the title "doctor".
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Promotion studies are ideally structured according to a preset time schedule of 4 to 6 years, during which the student has to be mentored by at least one professor.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The promotion study has to be concluded with at least a scientific thesis, which has to be defended to "a gathering of his/her peers", in practice the board of the faculty with guest professors from other faculties or universities added.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] More and more common—and, in some disciplines, even mandatory—is that the student write, and have accepted for publication by peer-reviewed journals, original scientific work.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The number of publications required is often debated and varies considerably between the various disciplines.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] However, in all disciplines the student is obligated to produce and publish a dissertation or thesis in book form.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] All current Dutch academic programs are offered under the Anglo-Saxon bachelor/master structure.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] It takes three years to earn a bachelor's degree and another one or two years to earn a master's degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] There are three official academic bachelor titles (BA, BSc and LLB) and three official master titles (MA, MSc and LLM).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] These academic titles are protected by the Dutch government.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] After obtaining a doctorate, Dutch doctors may bear either the title dr.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] (lower case) before, or the letter D following, their name, but not both simultaneously.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] There is no notation signifying the specific discipline in which the doctorate is obtained.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] As of 1 January 2021, the title 'PhD' and post-nominal degree 'PhD' can also be used, and these are also legally protected.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Stacking of titles, as seen in countries such as Germany (Prof.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Gruber), is highly uncommon in the Netherlands and not well received culturally.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Those who have multiple doctoral titles may use dr.mult. before their name, but this is seldom seen in practice.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The *honoris causa* doctors may use dr.h.c. before their name.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Combining different Dutch titles, especially in different disciplines, is allowed, however, (e.g. mr. dr.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The use of the combination ir. ing. is frequent, indicating one holds a HBO, vocational, or professional engineering degree "ing.", together with an academic engineering degree "ir.".
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] What is not allowed is, after obtaining a doctorate, using dr. drs.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] A combination of a Dutch title with an international title is not allowed, except for some limited number of international professional titles.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Thus, one should choose either one's classical Dutch title or use the shortcut provided by the law following one's name (since 1 September 2002 it is the other way around: those who hold Dutch degrees as MSc, LLM or MA may optionally use the old-style shortcuts before their names).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] "*Doctors*" (dr.) can proceed to teach at universities as "universitair docent" (UD – assistant professor).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] With time, experience and achievement, this can evolve to a position as "universitair hoofddocent" (UHD – associate professor).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Officially an UHD still works under the supervision of a "hoogleraar" (professor), the head of the department.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] However, this is not a given; it is also possible that a department is headed by a "plain" doctor, based on knowledge, achievement and expertise.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The position of "hoogleraar" is the highest possible scientific position at a university and equivalent to the US "full" professor.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The Dutch professor's title, noted as *prof.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Jansen* or *professor Jansen*, is connected to one's employment.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] This means that, should the professor leave the university, he or she also loses the privilege to use the title of professor.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Retired professors are an exception and may continue to note the title in front of their name, or use the title emeritus professor (em. prof.).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] People who switch to a non-university job lose their professorial title and are only allowed to use the "dr." abbreviation.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Unlike some other European countries, such as Germany, Dutch academic titles are used rarely outside academia, hold no value in everyday life, and typically are not listed on official documentation (e.g. passport, drivers license, (governmental) communication).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Dutch academic titles, however, are legally protected and can only be used by graduates from Dutch institutions of higher education.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Illegal use is considered a misdemeanor and is subject to legal prosecution.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Holders of foreign degrees, therefore, need special permission before being able to use a recognised Dutch title, but they are free to use their own foreign title (untranslated).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] In practice, the Public Department does not prosecute the illegal use of a protected title (the Netherlands applies prosecutorial discretion, so some known criminal uses are not prosecuted).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Prior to 1980, there were around 50 different degrees and corresponding educational programs within the Norwegian higher education system.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Degrees had titles that included the gender based Latin term *candidatus/candidata*.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The second part of the title usually consisted of a Latin word corresponding to the profession or training.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] (Candidatus Magisterii) required 4 to 5 years, Cand.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] (Candidatus Realium) required 6 years of study and a scientific thesis in a select set of scientific disciplines (realia).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Over the years these were replaced gradually with degrees that were more and more internationally comparable programs and corresponding titles.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] These degrees were all retired in 2003 in favour of an international system.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The reform of higher education in Norway, *Kvalitetsreformen* ("The Quality Reform"), was passed in the Norwegian Parliament, the Storting, in 2001 and carried out during the 2003/2004 academic year.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] It introduced standard periods of study and the titles *master* and *bachelor (baccalaureus)*.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The system differentiates between a free master's degree and a master's degree in technology.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The latter corresponds to the former *sivilingeniør* degree (not to be confused with a degree in civil engineering, which is but one of many degrees linked to the title *sivilingeniør*, which is still in use for new graduates who can choose to also use the old title).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] All pre-2001 doctoral degree titles were replaced with the title "Philosophical Doctor degree", written *philosophiæ doctor* (instead of the traditional *doctor philosophiæ*).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The title dr. philos. is a substantially higher degree than the PhD and is reserved for those who qualify for such a degree without participating in an organized doctoral degree program.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] In Poland, the system is similar to the German one.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Since 1992, Russian higher education has introduced a multilevel system, enabling higher education institutions to award and issue Bachelor of Science and Master of Science degrees.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] In Russia, Ukraine and some other former USSR republics educational degrees are awarded after finishing a college education.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] There are several levels of education that one must choose in the 2nd and 3rd year of college, usually in the 3rd year of study.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] A specialist degree is awarded after 5 years of college (4 + 1).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] A Master's (Magister) degree is awarded after 6 years of college (4 + 2).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] But a Specialist degree can appear equivalent to Magister degree by reason of taking an equivalent amount of time.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Usually Specialist or Magister degrees incorporate the bachelor's degrees in them, but only the high-level degree is given on the final diploma.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Specialist and Magister degrees require taking final state exams and producing written work on practical application of studied skills or research thesis (usually 70–100 pages) and is roughly equivalent to a master's degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The first-level academic degree is called *Candidate of Sciences* ("Kandidat Nauk").
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Finally, there is a *Doctor of Sciences* ("Doktor Nauk") degree in Russia and some former USSR academic environments.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] This degree is granted for contributions in a certain field (formally – who established new direction or new field in science).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] It requires discovery of new phenomenon or development of new theory or essential development of new direction, etc.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] There is no equivalent of this "doctor of sciences" degree in the US academic system.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] It is roughly equivalent to Habilitation in Germany, France, Austria and some other European countries.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] In countries with a two-tier system of doctoral degrees, the degree of *Candidate of Sciences* should be considered for recognition at the level of the first doctoral degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] According to *Guidelines for the recognition of Russian qualifications in the other countries*, in countries with a two-tier system of doctoral degrees, the degree of *Doktor Nauk* should be considered for recognition at the level of the second doctoral degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] In countries in which only one doctoral degree exists, the degree of *Doktor Nauk* should be considered for recognition at the level of this degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] LL.D. to *Candidate of Sciences of Legal Science*.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Spain's higher-education legal framework includes official and accredited education, as well as non-official education.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] In Spain, accreditation of official university study programmes is regulated by law and monitored by governmental agencies responsible for verifying their quality and suitability for official approval and accreditation.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Official professional study programmes lead to degree qualifications (*Títulos*) with full academic and professional rights.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Master's Degree (*Master Universitario*) – 60 to 120 ECTS Credits in 1–2 years.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Doctoral degree PhD (*Doctorado*) – in 3–4 years.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Accredited bachelor's degrees and master's degrees qualifications will always be described as *Grado* and *Master Universitario*.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] These qualifications comply with the European Higher Education Area (EHEA) framework.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Officially approved and accredited university study programmes by law must implement this framework in order to attain and retain accreditation in Spain.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Not all EHEA-compliant study programmes in Spain are officially approved or accredited by government agencies.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Some universities offer proprietary study programmes as alternatives for a variety of reasons: serving the continuing education market for individual self-advancement and also providing higher education to individuals who have failed to acquire bachelor's degree qualifications.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The main reason for offering these alternative studies, though, is the complex bureaucratic process required to receive the approval of specific titles, in particular when it refers to new studies or studies about matters that do not fit with the official studies.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] For historical reasons, the academic system has been very much under the control of the state, and private universities are still regarded with as a threat to the state system.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] These programmes fall within the category of "non officially approved and accredited" or *estudios no oficiales*, and they confer no academic or professional rights.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] This means that they do not entitle the bearer to claim to have any specific academic or professional qualifications, as far as the Spanish authorities are concerned.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] However, there may be private agreements to recognize the titles.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Universities offering non-official study programmes are legally bound to clearly differentiate between officially-approved and non-officially-approved qualifications.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Non-accredited master's degrees will be described as just *Master*, without the accompanying *Universitario*.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Certain non-officially approved and accredited study programmes may acquire a positive reputation.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] However, neither professional associations, government agencies, judiciary authorities, nor universities – other than the study programme provider – are obliged to recognize non-official qualifications in any way.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] All study programmes must be accredited by ANECA prior to their inclusion in the RUCT.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The RUCT records all officially approved universities and their bachelor's degrees, master's degrees and PhDs and each and every one of the officially approved and accredited study programmes.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Universities are assigned a specific number Code (*Código*) by the RUCT.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The same study programme may acquire different codes as it progresses through various stages of official approval by local and central governments.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Prospective students should check the RUCT Code awarded to the study programme of their interest at every stage of their enquiries concerning degrees in Spain.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] ANECA makes recommendations regarding procedures, staffing levels, quality of teaching, resources available to students and continuity or loss of accreditation.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The ANECA Registry records all events in the life of an officially approved and accredited study programme or a university.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The ANECA Registry Search Facility may be the simplest and safest way to verify the status of all officially approved and accredited study programmes in Spain.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] It is also possible to track qualifications by using the search facility that several Autonomous Communities' own accreditation agencies offer.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The qualifications framework for higher education MECES is the reference framework adopted in Spain in order to structure degree levels.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Not all universities offer degrees named exactly the same, even if they have similar academic and professional effects.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Each university may present proposals for the study programme considered to meet professional and academic demand.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] The proposal will consist of a report linking the study programme being considered and the proposed qualification to be awarded.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] This report will be assessed by ANECA and sent for the Consejo de Universidades Españolas.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] If the *Consejo* agrees with ANECA's approval, it will be included in the RUCT and ANECA registries.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] All bachelor's and master's degrees accredited by ANECA bestow full academic and professional rights in accordance with new and previous laws.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Professional-practice law in Spain is currently under revision.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Before the Bologna Process, the academic degree of a Licentiate was reached after 4 or 5 years of study.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Depending on the official language of the university, it was called *Lizentiat* (German), *Licence* (French) or *licenza* (Italian) and, according to the Bologna reform, is today considered equivalent to a master's degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] A Licentiate with a predefined qualification gave access to the last stage of a further two or more years of studies (depending on the field) for a doctoral degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Apart from this, most universities offered a postgraduate diploma requiring up to two years of study.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] French-speaking universities called them *diplôme d'études approfondies* DEA or DESS, the Italian-speaking university *post laurea* and German-speaking universities mostly *Nachdiplomstudium* (NDS).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Today the federal legislation defines these postgraduate diplomas (60 ECTS credits) as Master of Advanced Studies (MAS) or Executive Master of Business Administration (EMBA) degrees.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Universities may also offer the possibility to gain a diploma in advanced studies (DAS, less than 60 ECTS credits).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] These degrees do not normally give access to a doctoral programme.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Turkish education system has been mostly compatible with the Bologna process before and immediately after adoption.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] New graduates of a bachelor's program from Turkish law faculties are required to enter a legal licensing examination from 2022 onwards, in order to use all the rights to the extent that has been granted by the related laws.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p03] Such requirement does not exist for other degree holders.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] An academic degree is protected under UK law.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] All valid UK degrees are awarded by universities or other degree-awarding bodies whose powers to do so are recognised by the UK government; hence they are known as "recognised bodies".
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The standard first degree in England, Northern Ireland and Wales is the bachelor's degree conferred with honours.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Usually this is a Bachelor of Arts (BA) or a Bachelor of Science (BSc) degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Other variants exist: for example, Bachelor of Education or Bachelor of Laws.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] It usually takes three years to read for a bachelor's degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Candidates who have not achieved the standard for the award of honours may be admitted without honours to the "ordinary" bachelor's degree if they have met the required standard for this lesser qualification (also referred to as a "pass degree").
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Standard levels for each of these classes are 70%+ for a first, 60–69% for a 2:1, 50–59% for a 2:2, 40–49% for a 3rd and 30%+ for a pass degree, although this can vary by institution (e.g. the Open University).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The foundation degree is a qualification, lower than bachelor's level, awarded following a two-year programme of study that is usually vocational in nature.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The foundation degree can be awarded by a university or college of higher education that has been granted foundation-degree-awarding powers by the UK government.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] This degree is comparable to an associate degree in the United States.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The universities of Oxford and Cambridge award honorary Master of Arts (MA) degrees to graduates of their bachelor's programmes, following a specified period of time.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] This is comparable to the practice of the ancient universities in Scotland awarding an MA for a first degree and arguably reflects the rigorous standards expected of their graduates.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Master's degrees such as Master of Arts or Master of Science are typically awarded to students who have undertaken at least a year of full-time postgraduate study, which may require study and involve an element of research.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Degrees such as Master of Philosophy (MPhil) or Master of Letters/Literature (MLitt) are likely to be awarded for postgraduate study involving original research.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] A student undertaking a master's would normally be expected to already hold a bachelor's degree in a relevant subject, hence the possibility of reaching the master's level in one year.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Some universities award a master's as a first degree following an integrated programme of study (an 'integrated master's degree').
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] These degrees are usually designated by the subject, such as Master of Engineering for engineering, Master of Physics for physics, Master of Mathematics for mathematics and so on; it usually takes four years to read for them.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Graduation to these degrees is always with honours.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Master of Engineering in particular has now become the standard first degree in engineering at the top UK universities, replacing the older Bachelor of Engineering.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The Master of Business Administration (MBA) degree is highly valued by those seeking to advance in business as managers and decision makers.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Doctoral degrees or doctorates, such as the Doctor of Philosophy degree (PhD or DPhil) or Doctor of Education (EdD or DEd), are awarded following a programme of original research that contributes new knowledge within the context of the student's discipline.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Doctoral degrees usually take three years full-time.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Therefore, in the UK it may only take seven years to progress from undergraduate to earning a doctorate – in some cases six, since having a master's is not always a precondition for embarking on a doctoral degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] This contrasts with nine years in the United States, reflecting differences in the educational systems.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Some doctorates, such as the Doctor of Clinical Psychology (DClinPsy) qualification, confirm competence to practice in particular professions.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] UK post-secondary qualifications are defined at different levels, with levels 1–3 denoting further education and levels 4–8 denoting higher education.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Within this structure, a foundation degree is at level 5; a bachelor's degree at level 6; a master's degree at level 7; and a doctoral degree at level 8.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Full information about the expectations for different types of UK degrees is published by the Quality Assurance Agency for Higher Education.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] See also graduate certificate, graduate diploma, postgraduate certificate, postgraduate diploma and British degree abbreviations.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The standard first degree for students studying arts or humanities in Scotland is either a Bachelor of Arts or a Master of Arts (the latter traditionally awarded by the Ancient Universities of Scotland for a first degree in an arts/humanities subject).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The standard undergraduate degree for natural and social science subjects is the Bachelor of Science.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Students can work towards a first degree at either ordinary or honours level.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] A general or ordinary degree (BA/MA or BSc) takes three years to complete; an honours degree (BA/MA Hons or BSc Hons) takes four years.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The ordinary degree need not be in a specific subject, but can involve study across a range of subjects within (and sometimes beyond) the relevant faculty, in which case it may also be called a general degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] If a third year or junior honours subject is included, the ordinary degree in that named discipline is awarded.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The honours degree involves two years of study at a sub-honours level in which a range of subjects within the relevant faculty are studied and then two years of study at honours level which is specialised in a single field (for example classics, history, chemistry, biology, etc.).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Not all universities in Scotland adhere to this; in some, one studies in several subjects within a faculty for three years and can then specialise in two areas and attain a joint honours degree in fourth year.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] This also reflects the broader scope of the final years of Scottish secondary education, where traditionally five Highers are studied, compared to (typically) three English or Welsh A-Levels.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The Higher is a one-year qualification, as opposed to the two years of A-Levels, which accounts for Scottish honours degrees being a year longer than those in England.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Advanced Highers add an optional final year of secondary education, bringing students up to the level of their A-Level counterparts – students with strong A-Levels or Advanced Highers may be offered entry directly into the second year at Scottish universities.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Students who complete all the requirements for an honours degree, but who do not receive sufficient merit to be awarded third-class honours, may be awarded a *Special Degree* (ordinary degree – bachelor's level SCQF Level 9).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] In most respects, the criteria for awarding qualifications at honours level and above are the same as in the rest of the UK (see above under England, Wales and Northern Ireland).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Postgraduate qualifications are not designated Master of Arts, as in the rest of the UK, as this is an undergraduate degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Postgraduate degrees in arts and humanities subjects are usually designated Master of Letters (M.Litt.) or, in natural and social sciences, Master of Science (M.Sc.).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Non-doctoral postgraduate research degrees are usually designated Master of Philosophy (M.Phil.) or Master of Research (M.Res.).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The postgraduate teaching qualification is the Postgraduate Diploma in Education (PGDE).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] In Canada, education is the responsibility of the provinces and territories, rather than the federal government.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] However, all of Canada follows the three-level bachelor's-master's-doctorate system common to the Anglophone world, with a few variations.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] A common framework for degrees was agreed between the provinces and territories in 2007.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Bachelor's degrees take normally three to four years, more commonly three years in Quebec (where they follow on from college courses rather than directly from secondary education).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Outside Quebec, three-year bachelor's degrees are normally ordinary degrees, while four-year bachelor's degrees are honours degrees; an honours degree is normally needed for further study at the master's level.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Master's degrees take one to three years (in Quebec they normally take one and a half to two years).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Doctorates take a minimum of three years.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Alone among Canadian provinces and territories, British Columbia offers two-year associate degrees, allowing credit to be transferred into a four-year bachelor's program.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] In Canada, first professional degrees such as DDS, MD, PharmD and LLB or JD are considered bachelor's level qualifications, despite their often being named as if they were doctorates.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] In the province of Quebec, the majority of students must attend college prior to entering university.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Upon completion of a two-year pre-university program, such as in sciences or humanities, or a three-year technical program, such as nursing or computer science, college graduates obtain a *college diploma*, which is a prerequisite for access to university-level studies.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Although these college programs are typical, they are not offered in every institution in the province.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Moreover, while a few other pre-university programs with various concentrations exist, many other technical/career programs are available, depending on the college of choice.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] For example, Dawson College in Montreal has nearly sixty different programs leading to a college diploma.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Special programs, such as physical rehabilitation therapy, are offered in some colleges as well.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] A similar option is offered for college nursing graduates as they can pursue their studies in university to obtain a Bachelor of Nursing in two years (rather than the usual three or four years, depending on whether the student has completed a college diploma in Quebec).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Education in Mexico follows a three-degree system similar to that of Canada and the US.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The pre-university academic level is the *bachillerato* (also called *preparatoria*), similar to high school.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] They can also get the degree of "ingenieria" or "medico" as an engineer or MD, respectively.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] After receiving the *licenciatura*, students may take extra courses called *diplomados* (similar to a certification but issued by a university).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] These courses last 4–12 months and are a means to further study without continuing to the next degree level, and are usually to demonstrate that students are staying up-to-date in their fields.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Most students stay at this level, but some choose to continue to the *maestría*, equivalent to the master's degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Study at the *maestría* level takes 1–3 years and mandates completion of a thesis.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Post-graduate students in Mexico typically enter a master's program after a few years in the workforce and often continue working while studying.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Traditionally, students who have completed the *maestria* may continue on to the *doctorado* or the doctorate.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Doctoral study typically lasts 3–4 years.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] In recent years this schemes has become flexible such that in some PhD programmes, students are accepted before, or not completing, the course of study for a master's.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] In the United States, since the late 19th century, the threefold degree system of bachelor's, master's, and doctorate has been in place but has evolved into a slightly different pattern from the European equivalent.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Department of Education now classifies degrees in six categories: associate degrees, bachelor's degrees, first professional degrees, master's degrees, intermediate graduate qualifications and research doctorates.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The standard academic progression remains bachelor's—master's—(research) doctorate.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] This timetable is only approximate, however, as students in accelerated programs can sometimes earn a bachelor's degree in three years or, on the other hand, a particular dissertation project might take four or more years to complete.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] In addition, a graduate may wait an indeterminate time between degrees before candidacy in the next level or even an additional degree at a level already completed.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Therefore, there is no time limit on the accumulation of academic degrees.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] By far the most common research doctorate is the Doctor of Philosophy (Ph.D.), comprising 98.1% of research doctorates in 2014.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The Doctor of Education (Ed.D.) made up 1.1% (not including Ed.D.s classified as professional degrees rather than research doctorates) and all other research doctorates were less than 1% in total.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Some schools, mostly junior colleges and community colleges and some four-year schools, offer an associate degree that takes two full years of study.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] These may be in professional or academic fields, and the most common awards are the Associate of Arts (A.A.) and Associate of Science (A.S.) degrees.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Articulation agreements may allow credit earned on an associate degree to be counted toward the completion of a bachelor's degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The "first professional degree" is a graduate-level degree program designed to prepare graduates for professional practice in various fields other than academic scholarship and research.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] First professional degrees require a minimum of two years of college-level education prior to entering the program and a minimum of six years of total college-level education (including that undertaken prior to entry) to complete the program.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Most professional degree programs require a prior bachelor's degree for admission and many require seven or eight years of total study.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] M.D., J.D. or D.O. are named as doctorates but should not be confused with research doctorates such as the Ph.D.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] First professional degrees should also not be confused with professional master's degrees such as the M.Arch. and M.B.A., which are classified as master's degrees, or with intermediate graduate qualifications that also bear the title of doctor, such as D.Min. or D.Psy.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Intermediate graduate qualifications lie between the master's level and doctorate.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] They include awards such as the Certificate of Advanced Study, Graduate Diplomas, Professional Engineer status, and Professional Diplomas, as well as specialist degrees such as Education Specialist, Doctor of Ministry, Doctor of Psychology and the Licentiate in Sacred Theology.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] In 21 US jurisdictions, religious institutions can be authorized to grant religious-exempt (rel. exmpt., rel. expt., etc.) degrees without accreditation or government oversight.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Such degrees are used primarily to attain church-related employment.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Traditionally, more men than women attended and earned degrees at the world's universities.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] A milestone was reached in the United States, according to the 2010 census, as women surpassed men in attaining master's degrees, for the first time.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The U.S. census reports that 10.5 million men have master's degrees or higher, compared with 10.6 million women.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The first year that women surpassed men in earning bachelor's degrees was 1996.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Students, the media, and the general public have shown much concern over the value of getting a higher degree in the US ever since the Great Recession of 2007.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Media coverage of the rising costs of higher education and increased student debt have also affected the public's perceptions of whether higher degrees are still worthwhile.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Statistics citing that college graduates make around $1 million more in their lifetimes than those who did not attend college and live longer, healthier lives work in favor of those who argue the continued value of higher degrees.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Studies like the 2011 Learning Gains study by Arum and Roksa, on the other hand, reported that only 55% of students had any learning gains during their first two years of college, which favors the argument that investing in higher education may not still be worth it.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The Australian Qualifications Framework (AQF) covers 10 levels, of which levels 6–10 correspond to academic degrees.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Also included within the higher education system are: diplomas at level 5 (first year of a degree course); advanced diplomas, at level 6 (associate degree level); and graduate certificates and graduate diplomas, both of which are at level 8 (honours degree level).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] In Australia, most degrees are issued ungraded, with bachelor's degrees with honours being the exception.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Doctorates in Australia may be research doctorates (normally titled PhDs), professional doctorates (normally titled to refer to the field of practice, e.g.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Doctor of Engineering) or higher doctorates (also normally titled to refer to the field of practice).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Extended master's degrees are also allowed to have the word 'doctor' in their title if they are in certain fields, but they are not doctoral degrees.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Like Australia, New Zealand has a 10-level qualifications framework (the New Zealand Qualifications Framework – NZQF) and a referencing exercise has found a one-to-one correspondence between the levels of the two frameworks.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] However, the names given to qualifications at different levels are not the same and New Zealand does not have associate degrees, thus only levels 7–10 correspond to academic degrees.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] These are the bachelor's degree (level 7), bachelor honours degree (level 8), master's degree (level 9) and the doctoral degree (level 10).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] In addition to these, the NZQF has certificates across levels 1–6, diplomas at levels 5 and 6, graduate certificates and graduate diplomas at level 7 (bachelor's), and postgraduate certificates and postgraduate diplomas at level 8 (honours).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Another referencing exercise, comparing the NZQF to the 10-level Irish National Framework for Qualifications, found that degrees were comparable but that further work was needed to improve compatibility at the sub-degree levels (1–6).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Non-degree qualifications at levels 7–9 were not included in the study.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] In New Zealand, master's degrees may be awarded with classified honours (1st, 2:1, 2:2, 3rd) or with distinction or merit.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Undergraduate students in Brazilian universities graduate either with a bachelor's degree, a licentiate degree or a technologist degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Bachelor degrees in Brazil normally take four or five years of full-time study to complete, with the exception of the human medicine course, which requires six years.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Licentiate degrees normally take four-years, and are for students who want to qualify as school teachers.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] *Licenciatura* courses exist mostly in mathematics, humanities and natural sciences.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The technologist degree is available in technology-related fields and can be normally obtained in three years.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] These degrees are for entry into industry.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Admission as an undergraduate student to most top public or private universities in Brazil requires that the applicant pass a competitive entrance examination known as the Vestibular.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Contrary to what happens in the United States, candidates must declare their intended university major when they register for the Vestibular.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Although it is theoretically possible to switch majors afterwards (in a process known within the universities as *transferência interna*), that is actually quite rare in Brazil.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Undergraduate curricula tend to be more rigid than in the United States and there is little room to take classes outside one's major.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Individuals who hold either a bachelor's degree, licentiate or technologist are eligible for admission into graduate courses leading to advanced master's or doctor's degrees.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Criteria for admission into master's and doctor's programs vary in Brazil.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Some universities require that candidates take entrance exams; others make admission decisions based solely on undergraduate transcripts, letters of recommendation and possibly oral interviews.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] In most cases, however, especially for the doctorate, the candidate is required to submit a research plan, and one faculty member must agree to serve as supervisor before the candidate can be admitted into the program.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] There are two types of post-graduate programs: *lato sensu* (specialization and MBAs) and *stricto sensu* (professional master's, master's, and doctorate).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Specializations or MBAs are courses that include taking a minimum number of graduate classes (minimum of 360 hours) but with no need to do research nor defend a thesis, only to present final work showing knowledge acquired.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] It is a professional level where theory and practice are focused broadly.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Professional master's or master's degrees usually take one to two years of full-time study.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The emphasis of the thesis must be in adding some value to knowledge, but not necessarily in being original.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Doctoral degrees normally take four additional years of full-time study to complete.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Requirements for obtaining a doctor's degree include taking additional advanced courses, passing an oral qualifying exam, and submitting a longer doctoral dissertation which must represent a significant original contribution to knowledge in the field to which the dissertation topic is related.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] That contrasts with master's thesis, which, in addition to being usually shorter than doctoral dissertations, are not required to include creation of new knowledge or revision/reinterpretation of older views/theories.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The doctoral dissertation is examined in a final oral exam before a panel of at least two members (in the state of São Paulo the preferred number is five, while the other regions prefer three members), usually including one or two external examiners from another university or research institute.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] In Colombia, the system of academic degrees is based in the British model, similar to the U.S. model.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] After completing their "bachillerato" (high school), students can take one of three options.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The first one is called a *profesional* (professional career), which is similar to a bachelor's degree requiring from four to 6 years of study according to the chosen program.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The other option is called a *técnico* (technician); this degree consists of two and a half years of study and prepares the student for technical or mechanical labors.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Finally, the third option is called a *tecnólogo* (equivalent to associate degree) and consists of three years of study.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] After this, students, now called *profesional* (professionals), *técnicos* (technicians) or *tecnólogos* (associates), can opt for higher degrees.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Formal education after the bachelor's degree leads to the master's degree with the title of *maestro* and doctorate degrees, known as *doctorado* (doctorate).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The master's degree normally takes two years.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Students also can take a specialization course, *especialización*, equivalent to a graduate certificate degree, after their bachelor's degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] These programs, like in the U.S., are very popular, because it requires only one to two years of study.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] In Colombia, similar to the U.S. system, the students may not go directly to the *doctorado* without having the "master" degree first.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] After completing *enseñanza media* (high school), students receive a *Licenciatura de Enseñanza Media* (high school diploma), which is a requirement for higher education.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Higher-education programs that provide a professional title but not an academic degree are referred to as *carreras técnicas*, which are similar in duration and scope to associate degree programs.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] These are often granted by educational institutions of the type *instituto profesional* (IP) or *centro de formación técnica* (CFT).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Academic degrees in Venezuela start with the *Certificado de Educación Básica* (Certificate of Basic Education), awarded upon completing the 9th grade.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The next degree is earned upon completing the 11th grade and confers the title of *Bachiller en Ciencias* (High School Graduate of Science), *Bachiller en Humanidades* (High School Graduate of Humanities) or *Técnico en Ciencias* (Science Technician).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Titles at the higher-education level usually depend on the institution handing them out.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Technical schools award the student with the title of *Técnico Superior Universitario* (university higher technician, to distinguish from science technician).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Universities award the student with the title of *ingeniero* (engineer) or with the title *licenciado* (licentiate) after completing a five-year program.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The ingeniero degree requires more physics than the licenciado degree, but both take five years.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Some higher-education institutions may award *diplomados* (diploma), but the time necessary to obtain one varies.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Medical doctors are awarded the title "Médico Cirujano" after completing a 6-year course of study.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] Postgraduate education in Venezuela follows the conventions of the United States (being named "master's" and "doctorate" after the programs there).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The nature of academic degrees from ecclesiastical institutions of education is outlined in the apostolic constitution *Sapientia Christiana*.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-degree-p04] The core of degrees granted by pontifical universities consists of three levels: the first is the baccalaureate; the second is the licentiate; the third is the doctorate.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] An **academic discipline** or **academic field** is a subdivision of knowledge that is taught and researched at the college or university level.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Disciplines are defined (in part) and recognized by the academic journals in which research is published, and the learned societies and academic departments or faculties within colleges and universities to which their practitioners belong.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Academic disciplines are conventionally divided into the humanities (including philosophy, languages, art and cultural studies), the natural sciences (such as physics, chemistry, and biology); and the formal sciences like mathematics and computer science.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] The social sciences are sometimes considered a fourth category.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] It is also known as a *field of study*, *field of inquiry*, *research field* and *branch of knowledge*.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] The different terms are used in different countries and fields.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Individuals associated with academic disciplines are commonly referred to as *experts* or *specialists*.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Others, who may have studied liberal arts or systems theory rather than concentrating in a specific academic discipline, are classified as *generalists*.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] For example, professionals may encounter trouble communicating across academic disciplines because of differences in jargon, concepts, or methodology.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Some researchers believe that academic disciplines may, in the future, be replaced by what is known as Mode 2 or "post-academic science", which involves the acquisition of cross-disciplinary knowledge through the collaboration of specialists from various academic disciplines.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] The University of Paris in 1231 consisted of four faculties:- Theology, Medicine, Canon Law and Arts.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Educational institutions originally used the term "discipline" to catalog and archive the new and expanding body of information produced by the scholarly community.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Disciplinary designations originated in German universities during the beginning of the nineteenth century.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] In the early twentieth century, new academic disciplines such as education and psychology were added.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] In the 1970s and 1980s, there was an explosion of new academic disciplines focusing on specific themes, such as media studies, women's studies, and Africana studies.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Many academic disciplines designed as preparation for careers and professions, such as nursing, hospitality management, and corrections, also emerged in the universities.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Finally, interdisciplinary scientific fields of study such as biochemistry and geophysics gained prominence as their contribution to knowledge became widely recognized.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Some new disciplines, such as public administration, can be found in more than one disciplinary setting; some public administration programs are associated with business schools (thus emphasizing management), while others are linked to political science (emphasizing policy analysis).
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] As the twentieth century approached, these designations were gradually adopted by other countries and became the accepted conventional subjects.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] However, these designations differed between various countries.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] In the twentieth century, the natural science disciplines included: physics, chemistry, biology, geology, and astronomy.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] The social science disciplines included: economics, politics, sociology, and psychology.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Prior to the twentieth century, categories were broad and general, which was expected due to the lack of interest in science at the time.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Most practitioners of science were amateurs and were referred to as "natural historians" and "natural philosophers"—labels that date back to Aristotle—instead of "scientists".
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Natural history referred to what we now call life sciences and natural philosophy referred to the current physical sciences.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Prior to the twentieth century, few opportunities existed for science as an occupation outside the educational system.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Higher education provided the institutional structure for scientific investigation, as well as economic support for research and teaching.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Soon, the volume of scientific information rapidly increased and researchers realized the importance of concentrating on smaller, narrower fields of scientific activity.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Because of this narrowing, scientific specializations emerged.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] As these specializations developed, modern scientific disciplines in universities also improved their sophistication.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Eventually, academia's identified disciplines became the foundations for scholars of specific specialized interests and expertise.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] An influential critique of the concept of academic disciplines came from Michel Foucault in his 1975 book, *Discipline and Punish*.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Communities of academic disciplines can be found outside academia within corporations, government agencies, and independent organizations, where they take the form of associations of professionals with common interests and specific knowledge.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Such communities include corporate think tanks, NASA, and IUPAC.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Communities such as these exist to benefit the organizations affiliated with them by providing specialized new ideas, research, and findings.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Nations at various developmental stages will find the need for different academic disciplines during different times of growth.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] A newly developing nation will likely prioritize government, political matters and engineering over those of the humanities, arts and social sciences.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] On the other hand, a well-developed nation may be capable of investing more in the arts and social sciences.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Communities of academic disciplines would contribute at varying levels of importance during different stages of development.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] These categories explain how the different academic disciplines interact with one another.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Multidisciplinary (or pluridisciplinary) knowledge is associated with more than one existing academic discipline or profession.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] A multidisciplinary community or project is made up of people from different academic disciplines and professions.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] One key question is how well the challenge can be decomposed into subparts, and then addressed via the distributed knowledge in the community.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] The lack of shared vocabulary between people and communication overhead can sometimes be an issue in these communities and projects.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] If challenges of a particular type need to be repeatedly addressed so that each one can be properly decomposed, a multidisciplinary community can be exceptionally efficient and effective.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] There are many examples of a particular idea appearing in different academic disciplines, all of which came about around the same time.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] One example of this scenario is the shift from the approach of focusing on sensory awareness of the whole, "an attention to the 'total field'", a "sense of the whole pattern, of form and function as a unity", an "integral idea of structure and configuration".
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] This has happened in art (in the form of cubism), physics, poetry, communication and educational theory.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] According to Marshall McLuhan, this paradigm shift was due to the passage from the era of mechanization, which brought sequentiality, to the era of the instant speed of electricity, which brought simultaneity.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Multidisciplinary approaches also encourage people to help shape the innovation of the future.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] The political dimensions of forming new multidisciplinary partnerships to solve the so-called societal Grand Challenges were presented in the Innovation Union and in the European Framework Programme, the Horizon 2020 operational overlay.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Innovation across academic disciplines is considered the pivotal foresight of the creation of new products, systems, and processes for the benefit of all societies' growth and wellbeing.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Regional examples such as Biopeople and industry-academia initiatives in translational medicine such as SHARE.ku.dk in Denmark provide evidence of the successful endeavour of multidisciplinary innovation and facilitation of the paradigm shift.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] In practice, transdisciplinary can be thought of as the union of all interdisciplinary efforts.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] While interdisciplinary teams may be creating new knowledge that lies between several existing disciplines, a transdisciplinary team is more holistic and seeks to relate all disciplines into a coherent whole.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Cross-disciplinary knowledge is that which explains aspects of one discipline in terms of another.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Common examples of cross-disciplinary approaches are studies of the physics of music or the politics of literature.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Bibliometrics can be used to map several issues in relation to disciplines, for example, the flow of ideas within and among disciplines (Lindholm-Romantschuk, 1998) or the existence of specific national traditions within disciplines.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] Scholarly impact and influence of one discipline on another may be understood by analyzing the flow of citations.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] The Bibliometrics approach is described as straightforward because it is based on simple counting.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] The method is also objective but the quantitative method may not be compatible with a qualitative assessment and therefore manipulated.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-discipline] The number of citations is dependent on the number of persons working in the same domain instead of inherent quality or published result's originality.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] Tenure was introduced into American universities in the early 1900s in part to prevent the arbitrary dismissal of faculty members who expressed unpopular views.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] Before Nazism, Germany had been a leader in academic tenure, but free speech and tenure were severely curtailed under the Third Reich.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] Adolf Hitler called universal education "the most corroding and disintegrating poison".
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] He appointed Education Minister Bernhard Rust, to ensure Nazi racial theories were integrated in university curriculums.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] This caused a purge of 1500 professors, and by 1939, nearly half of all faculty posts were occupied by Nazis.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] In the late 1940s, the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign fired several untenured economists, all of whom subsequently had distinguished careers, for teaching the "heresy" Keynesian economics.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] Danish universities in advertisements for faculty positions usually state that professor positions are tenured.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] What that means has been a matter of controversy.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] Denmark adopted a more hierarchical management approach for universities in the early 2000s.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] This new system was introduced by parliament on a proposal by the Minister of Science, Technology and Development, Helge Sander, based on his vision that Danish universities should compete for funding in order to increase their attention to marketing and industry.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] Thybo disputed the causes of his firing, and the postdoc said that he did not feel pressured.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] The handling of the firing was criticized by other researchers.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] A later court decision ruled that the dismissal had not followed the collective agreements and Thybo received economic compensation.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] Thybo had insisted that he should be reinstated in his previous position, but this was not supported by the court and the university did not rehire him.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] The original form of academic tenure was removed in the United Kingdom in 1988 through the Education Reform Act.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] In its place, there is the distinction between permanent and temporary contracts for academics.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] A permanent lecturer in UK universities usually holds an open-ended position that covers teaching, research and administrative responsibilities.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] In 2010, 9% of academic staff were professors, 66% were "junior staff" (including doctoral candidates on contracts), and 25% were other academic staff in secondary employment.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] Permanent research, teaching and management positions below professorship as an "Akademischer Rat" (a civil service position salaried like high school teachers) have become relatively rare compared to the 1970s and 1980s and are often no longer refilled after a retirement.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] This means that, compared to other countries, academics in Germany obtain tenure at a relatively late age, as on average one becomes an Academic Assistant at the age of 42.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] In 2002 the "Juniorprofessur" position (comparable to an assistant professor in the US, but not always endowed with a tenure track) was introduced as an alternative to "Habilitation".
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] Due to a university system that guarantees universities relative academic freedom, the position of professor in Germany is relatively strong and independent.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] As civil servants, professors have a series of attendant rights and benefits, yet this status is subject to discussion.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] In the W pay scale the professorial pay is related to performance rather than merely to age, as it was in C.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] Under the tenure systems adopted by many universities and colleges in the United States and Canada, some faculty positions have tenure and some do not.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] This statement holds that, "The common good depends upon the free search for truth and its free exposition" and stresses that academic freedom is essential in teaching and research in this regard.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] The statement limits the number of years that any employee can remain employed as a non-tenured instructor or professor, compelling the institution to grant tenure to or terminate an individual, with significant advance notice, at the end of a specified time period.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] Some institutions require promotion to associate professor as a condition of tenure.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] A university may also offer research positions or professional track and clinical track academic positions which are said to be "non-tenure track".
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] Positions with titles such as instructor, lecturer, adjunct professor, research professor etc. do not carry the possibility of tenure, have higher teaching loads, have less influence within the institution, lower compensation with few or no benefits and little protection of academic freedom.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] In the United States, tenure rights for teachers serving in K-12 public schools also have been in existence for more than a hundred years, beginning first in New Jersey in 1909..
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] Defenders of tenure, like Ellen Schrecker and Aeon J.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] "Tenure remains scholars' best defense of free inquiry and heterodoxy," writes Skoble, "especially in these times of heightened polarization and internet outrage.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] Moreover, there is no way that the employing institution can provide the kind of retraining that would facilitate such a transformation... even the largest and most well-endowed institution lacks the resources to reevaluate and replace its medieval Islamicists and algebraic topologists every year.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] Tenure thus lets the academic community avoid excessive turnover while still ensuring the quality of the institution's faculty.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] To Bruce, this is an argument against tenure, but my point is that the more I am persuaded that there is groupthink orthodoxy afoot, the more I want assurances that I would not get fired if I write an essay on free trade or the Second Amendment or a book on anarchism.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] I take it the counterargument is that the more entrenched the orthodoxy becomes, the less likely a heterodox scholar will be tenured, or even hired, in the first place...
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] I can see that this poses a problem but fail to see how abolishing tenure would help.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] As things stand, some heterodox scholars do get hired and tenured..
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] Skoble argues categorically and plainly against critics that say "tenure protects incompetent professors": "My argument is that when this happens, it is a malfunction of the system, not an intrinsic feature of its proper use.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] The way it is supposed to work is that incompetent professors do not get tenure in the first place.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] Some have argued that modern tenure systems diminish academic freedom, forcing those seeking tenured positions to profess conformance to the level of mediocrity as those awarding the tenured professorships.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] Economist Steven Levitt, who recommends the elimination of tenure (for economics professors) in order to incentivize higher performance among professors, also points out that a pay increase may be required to compensate faculty members for the lost job security.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] Organizational theorist Russel Ackoff did not believe in it, and went as far as to deposit a signed but undated resignation letter with the Dean of the Wharton School, to be used if and when the Dean thought it could be appropriate to do so.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] Some U.S. states have considered legislation to remove tenure at public universities.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] A further criticism of tenure is that it rewards complacency.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] Once professors are awarded tenure, they may begin putting reduced effort into their job, knowing that their removal is difficult or expensive to the institution.
[src:bachelor-of-science/academic-tenure] Another criticism is that it may cause the institution to tolerate incompetent professors if they are tenured.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] An ***ad eundem* degree** is an academic degree awarded by one university or college to an alumnus of another, in a process commonly known as **incorporation**.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] An *ad eundem* degree is not an earned degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] In the later Middle Ages it was common, when a graduate from one university moved into the neighborhood of another, for the new university to admit the graduate as a courtesy, "at the same degree" (in Latin, *ad eundem gradum*).
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] Thus if someone was a Bachelor of Arts in the university that they had attended, they would likewise be a bachelor of arts of their new university.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] Not every college extended this courtesy to all other colleges, however.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] The practice of incorporation diminished in the early 19th century, but it continues at the University of Oxford, the University of Cambridge, and Trinity College Dublin.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] Requests for *ad eundem gradum* degrees also occurred at Adelaide University in the 1880s.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] A number of female students at Oxford and Cambridge were awarded *ad eundem* University of Dublin degrees at Trinity College Dublin, between 1904 and 1907, at a time when their own universities refused to confer degrees upon women and were nicknamed the "steamboat ladies".
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] Today, graduates of the Universities of Oxford and Cambridge are eligible to apply for corresponding degrees of Trinity College Dublin, and vice versa, provided that they wish to register for a degree at Trinity College or are members of the academic staff, and pay the required fee.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] Rhodes University in South Africa uses the term *ad eundem gradum* to give a student status to undertake a research higher degree based on experience, as opposed to an explicit qualification.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] In this case the student does not acquire a qualification, but is exempt from an entry requirement.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] At the University of Oxford, incorporation first appeared in the University Statutes in 1516, although the practice itself is older: in the 15th and early 16th centuries, incorporation was granted to members of universities from all over Europe.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] In 1861, incorporation was restricted to members of Cambridge University and Trinity College, Dublin.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] In 1908, incorporation was further restricted to specific degrees from these universities.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] While not an earned degree, both original degree(s) and incorporated *ad eundem* degree(s) are given in post-nominals listed in the Oxford University Calendar.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] These attempts were rebuffed by the other universities, and eventually abandoned by Durham.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] Still, Durham granted graduates from other universities degrees *ad eundem* until the practice was abolished by the adoption of new university statutes in 1909.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] In the United States, the *ad eundem* Bachelor of Arts and Master of Arts as a regularly awarded academic qualification from graduates of other colleges and universities generally dates from the colonial period, and was awarded at the institutions listed below.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] Five universities in the United States follow a tradition that only alumni may hold certain faculty positions, and in limited cases preserve the tradition of the *ad eundem* Master of Arts to the present day, with the specific circumstances described below.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] Because these degrees do not involve any further study, many faculty members do not list them on their curricula vitae, although some choose to do so.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] At Harvard the degree is described as given *ut in grege nostro numeretur* ("so that (s)he may be numbered in our flock").
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] At Brown, the degrees have been awarded as a part of the annual May commencement ceremony.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] At Amherst, Wesleyan, and Yale, the degrees are conferred upon those who rise to the rank of full professor.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] Yale refers to this degree as the MA *Privatim*.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] During the 150th anniversary of Princeton University, in 1896, 16 full professors were awarded the MA *Privatim*.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] At Amherst, in recent years, the degrees are awarded during first-year student convocation in August, at Yale it is an "elegant, brief ceremony, usual in February or March", and at Wesleyan as part of commencement in May.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] Amherst College grants this degree to college faculty despite the fact that it grants only bachelor's degrees to its matriculated students.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] However, those professors who already earned a bachelor's degree at Amherst or Wesleyan by attending as an undergraduate are not presented with a second degree.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] In 2024, Amherst College President Michael A.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] In April 2023, the President of Yale, Peter Salovey, awarded M.A.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] *Privatim* degrees posthumously to Reverend James W.
[src:bachelor-of-science/ad-eundem-degree] Pennington and Reverend Alexander Crummell, the first two black students at Yale, both of whom faced numerous incidents of discrimination and left Yale without earning degrees.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Human habitation in Afghanistan dates to the Middle Paleolithic era.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Popularly referred to as the graveyard of empires, the land has witnessed numerous military campaigns, including those by the Persians, Alexander the Great, the Maurya Empire, Arab Muslims, the Mongols, the British, the Soviet Union, and a US-led coalition.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan also served as the source from which the Greco-Bactrians and the Mughals, among others, rose to form major empires.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Because of the various conquests and periods in both the Iranian and Indian cultural spheres, the area was a center for Zoroastrianism, Buddhism, Hinduism, and later Islam.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The modern state of Afghanistan began with the Durrani Empire in the 18th century under Ahmad Shah Durrani, although Dost Mohammad Khan is sometimes considered to be the founder of the first modern Afghan state.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan became a buffer state in the Great Game between the British Empire and the Russian Empire.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] From India, the British attempted to subjugate Afghanistan but were repelled in the First Anglo-Afghan War; the Second Anglo-Afghan War saw a British victory.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Following the Third Anglo-Afghan War in 1919, Afghanistan became free of foreign political hegemony, and emerged as the independent Kingdom of Afghanistan in 1926; this monarchy lasted almost half a century.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Since the late 1970s, Afghanistan's history has been dominated by extensive warfare, including coups, invasions, insurgencies, and civil wars.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] This period of instability began in 1973 when King Zahir Shah was overthrown by his cousin Mohammad Daoud Khan, ending the monarchy and resulting in the establishment of the Republic of Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Daoud Khan became the President of Afghanistan, ruling as an autocrat.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] In 1978 the conflict became a violent one when a communist revolution overthrew and assassinated Daoud Khan, establishing the socialist Democratic Republic of Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Subsequent infighting prompted the Soviet Union to invade Afghanistan in 1979.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The *mujahideen* won against the Soviets in the Soviet–Afghan War, leading to the Soviets' withdrawal in 1989.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The ensuing civil war overthrew the socialist republic and established the Islamic State of Afghanistan through the Peshawar Accord, which could not remain in force and resulted in a second civil war between *mujahideen* factions in 1992.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban controlled most of the country by 1996, but their Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan received little international recognition before its overthrow in the 2001 US invasion of Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban returned to power in 2021 after capturing Kabul, ending the 2001–2021 war.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban government is widely unrecognized by the international community due to reported violations of human rights in Afghanistan, particularly regarding the treatment of women by the Taliban.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan is rich in natural resources, including lithium, iron, zinc, and copper.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] It is the third largest producer of both saffron and cashmere.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The country is a member of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation and a founding member of the Organization of Islamic Cooperation.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Due to the effects of war in recent decades, the country has dealt with high levels of terrorism, poverty, and child malnutrition.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan remains among the world's least developed countries with its economic output per capita among the lowest of any country.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Some scholars suggest that the root name *Afghān* is derived from the Sanskrit word *Aśvakan*, which was the name used for ancient inhabitants of the Hindu Kush.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] *Aśvakan* literally means "horsemen", "horse breeders", or "cavalrymen" (from *aśva*, the Sanskrit and Avestan words for "horse").
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Historically, the ethnonym *Afghān* was used to refer to ethnic Pashtuns.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Arabic and Persian form of the name, *Afġān*, was first attested in the 10th-century geography book *Hudud al-'Alam*.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The last part of the name, "*-stan*", is a Persian suffix meaning "place of".
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Therefore, "Afghanistan" translates to "land of the Afghans", or "land of the Pashtuns" in a historical sense.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The term "Afghanistan" was officially used in 1855, when the British recognized Dost Mohammad Khan as king of Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Excavations of prehistoric sites suggest that humans were living in what is now Afghanistan at least 50,000 years ago, and that farming communities in the area were among the earliest in the world.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] An important site of early historical activities, many believe that Afghanistan compares to Egypt in the historical value of its archaeological sites.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Artifacts typical of the Paleolithic, Mesolithic, Neolithic, Bronze, and Iron Ages have been found in Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Urban civilization is believed to have begun as early as 3000 BCE, and the early city of Mundigak (near Kandahar in the south of the country) was a center of the Helmand culture.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] More recent findings established that the Indus Valley Civilization stretched up towards modern-day Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] An Indus Valley site has been found on the Oxus River at Shortugai in northern Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] After 2000 BCE successive waves of semi-nomadic people from Central Asia began moving south into Afghanistan; among them were many Indo-European-speaking Indo-Iranians.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] These tribes later migrated further into South Asia, Western Asia, and toward Europe via the area north of the Caspian Sea.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The region at the time was referred to as Ariana.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] By the middle of the 6th century BCE, the Achaemenids overthrew the Medes and incorporated Arachosia, Aria, and Bactria within its eastern boundaries.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] An inscription on the tombstone of Darius I of Persia mentions the Kabul Valley in a list of the 29 countries that he had conquered.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The region of Arachosia, around Kandahar in modern-day southern Afghanistan, used to be primarily Zoroastrian and played a key role in the transfer of the Avesta to Persia and is thus considered by some to be the "second homeland of Zoroastrianism".
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Alexander the Great and his Macedonian forces arrived in Afghanistan in 330 BCE after defeating Darius III of Persia a year earlier in the Battle of Gaugamela.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Following Alexander's brief occupation, the successor state of the Seleucid Empire controlled the region until 305 BCE, when they gave much of it to the Maurya Empire as part of an alliance treaty.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Mauryans controlled the area south of the Hindu Kush until they were overthrown in about 185 BCE.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Their decline began 60 years after Ashoka's rule ended, leading to the Hellenistic reconquest by the Greco-Bactrians.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Much of it soon broke away and became part of the Indo-Greek Kingdom.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] They were defeated and expelled by the Indo-Scythians in the late 2nd century BCE.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Silk Road appeared during the first century BCE, and Afghanistan flourished with trade, with routes to China, India, Persia, and north to the cities of Bukhara, Samarkand, and Khiva in present-day Uzbekistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Goods and ideas were exchanged at this center point, such as Chinese silk, Persian silver and Roman gold, while the region of present Afghanistan was mining and trading lapis lazuli stones mainly from the Badakhshan region.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] During the first century BCE, the Parthian Empire subjugated the region but lost it to their Indo-Parthian vassals.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] In the mid-to-late first century CE the vast Kushan Empire, centered in Afghanistan, became great patrons of Buddhist culture, making Buddhism flourish throughout the region.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Kushans were overthrown by the Sassanids in the 3rd century CE, though the Indo-Sassanids continued to rule at least parts of the region.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] They were followed by the Kidarites who, in turn, was replaced by the Hephthalites.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] They were replaced by the Turk Shahi in the 7th century.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Buddhist Turk Shahi of Kabul was replaced by a Hindu dynasty before the Saffarids conquered the area in 870; this Hindu dynasty was called Hindu Shahi.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Much of the northeastern and southern areas of the country remained dominated by Buddhist culture.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Arab Muslims brought Islam to Herat and Zaranj in 642 CE and began spreading eastward; some of the native inhabitants they encountered accepted it while others revolted.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Before the arrival of Islam, the region used to be home to various beliefs and cults, often resulting in Syncretism between the dominant religions such as Zoroastrianism, Buddhism or Greco-Buddhism, Ancient Iranian religions, Hinduism, Christianity, and Judaism.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] An exemplification of the syncretism in the region would be that people were patrons of Buddhism but still worshipped local Iranian gods such as Ahura Mazda, Lady Nana, Anahita or Mihr (Mithra) and portrayed Greek gods as protectors of Buddha.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Zunbils and Kabul Shahi were first conquered in 870 CE by the Saffarid Muslims of Zaranj.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Later, the Samanids extended their Islamic influence south of the Hindu Kush.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Ghaznavids rose to power in the 10th century.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] By the 11th century, Mahmud of Ghazni had defeated the remaining Hindu rulers and effectively Islamized the wider region, with the exception of Kafiristan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Mahmud made Ghazni into an important city and patronized intellectuals such as the historian al-Biruni and the poet Ferdowsi.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Ghaznavid dynasty was overthrown by the Ghurids in 1186, whose architectural achievements included the remote Minaret of Jam.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Ghurids controlled Afghanistan for less than a century before being conquered by the Khwarazmian dynasty in 1215.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] In 1219 CE, Genghis Khan and his Mongol army overran the region.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] His troops are said to have annihilated the Khwarazmian cities of Herat and Balkh as well as Bamyan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The destruction caused by the Mongols forced many locals to return to an agrarian rural society.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Mongol rule continued with the Ilkhanate in the northwest while the Khalji dynasty administered the Afghan tribal areas south of the Hindu Kush until the invasion of Timur (aka Tamerlane), who established the Timurid Empire in 1370.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Under the rule of Shah Rukh, the city of Herat served as the focal point of the Timurid Renaissance, whose glory matched Florence of the Italian Renaissance as the center of a cultural rebirth.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] In the early 16th century Babur arrived from Ferghana and captured Kabul from the Arghun dynasty.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Babur would go on to conquer the Afghan Lodi dynasty who had ruled the Delhi Sultanate in the First Battle of Panipat.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Between the 16th and 18th century, the Uzbek Khanate of Bukhara, Iranian Safavids, and Indian Mughals ruled parts of the territory.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] During the medieval period, the northwestern area of Afghanistan was referred to by the regional name Khorasan, which was commonly used up to the 19th century among natives to describe their country.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] In 1709, Mirwais Hotak, a local Ghilzai tribal leader, successfully rebelled against the Safavids.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] He defeated Gurgin Khan, the Georgian governor of Kandahar under the Safavids, and established his own kingdom.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Mirwais died in 1715, and was succeeded by his brother Abdul Aziz, who was soon killed by Mirwais's son Mahmud for possibly planning to sign a peace with the Safavids.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Mahmud led the Afghan army in 1722 to the Persian capital of Isfahan, and captured the city after the Battle of Gulnabad and proclaimed himself King of Persia.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Afghan dynasty was ousted from Persia by Nader Shah after the 1729 Battle of Damghan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] In 1738, Nader Shah and his forces captured Kandahar in the siege of Kandahar, the last Hotak stronghold, from Shah Hussain Hotak.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Soon after, the Persian and Afghan forces invaded India, Nader Shah had plundered Delhi, alongside his 16-year-old commander, Ahmad Shah Durrani who had assisted him on these campaigns.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Ahmad Shah had launched two campaigns into Khorasan, 1750–1751 and 1754–1755.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] By the early 19th century, the Afghan empire was under threat from the Persians in the west and the Sikh Empire in the east.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Fateh Khan, leader of the Barakzai tribe, installed many of his brothers in positions of power throughout the empire.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Fateh Khan was brutally murdered in 1818 by Mahmud Shah.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] As a result, the brothers of Fateh Khan and the Barakzai tribe rebelled, and a civil war brewed.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] During this turbulent period, Afghanistan fractured into many states, including the Principality of Qandahar, Emirate of Herat, Khanate of Qunduz, Maimana Khanate, and numerous other warring polities.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The most prominent state was the Emirate of Kabul, ruled by Dost Mohammad Khan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Akbar Khan and the Afghan army failed to capture the Jamrud Fort from the Sikh Khalsa Army, but killed Sikh commander Hari Singh Nalwa, thus ending the Afghan-Sikh Wars.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] In 1893, Abdur Rahman signed an agreement in which the ethnic Pashtun and Baloch territories were divided by the Durand Line, which forms the modern-day border between Pakistan and Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Shia-dominated Hazarajat and pagan Kafiristan remained politically independent until being conquered by Abdur Rahman Khan in 1891–1896.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] He was known as the "Iron Amir" for his features and his ruthless methods against tribes.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] He died in 1901, succeeded by his son, Habibullah Khan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] During the First World War, when Afghanistan was neutral, Habibullah Khan was met by officials of the Central Powers in the Niedermayer–Hentig Expedition.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] They called on Afghanistan to declare full independence from the United Kingdom, join them and attack British India, as part of the Hindu–German Conspiracy.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The effort to bring Afghanistan into the Central Powers failed, but it sparked discontent among the population about maintaining neutrality with the British.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Habibullah was assassinated in February 1919, and Amanullah Khan eventually assumed power.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] A staunch supporter of the 1915–1916 expeditions, Amanullah Khan invaded British India, beginning the Third Anglo-Afghan War, and entering British India via the Khyber Pass.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Following the end of the Third Anglo-Afghan War and the signing of the Treaty of Rawalpindi on 19 August 1919, Emir Amanullah Khan declared the Emirate of Afghanistan a sovereign and fully independent state.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] He moved to end his country's traditional isolation by establishing diplomatic relations with the international community, particularly with the Soviet Union and the Weimar Republic.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] He proclaimed himself King of Afghanistan on 9 June 1926, forming the Kingdom of Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] He introduced several reforms intended to modernize his nation.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] A key force behind these reforms was Mahmud Tarzi, an ardent supporter of the education of women.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] He fought for Article 68 of Afghanistan's 1923 constitution, which implemented compulsory elementary education.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] King Amanullah's wife, Queen Soraya, was an important figure during this period in the fight for women's education and against their oppression.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Some of the reforms, such as the abolition of the traditional burqa for women and the opening of co-educational schools, alienated many tribal and religious leaders, leading to the Afghan Civil War (1928–1929).
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] King Amanullah abdicated in January 1929, and soon after Kabul fell to Saqqawist forces led by Habibullah Kalakani.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Mohammad Nadir Shah, Amanullah's cousin, defeated and killed Kalakani in October 1929, and was declared King Nadir Shah.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] He abandoned the reforms of King Amanullah in favor of a more gradual approach to modernization, but was assassinated in 1933 by Abdul Khaliq.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Mohammed Zahir Shah succeeded to the throne and reigned as king from 1933 to 1973.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] During the tribal revolts of 1944–1947, King Zahir's reign was challenged by Zadran, Safi, Mangal, and Wazir tribesmen led by Mazrak Zadran, Salemai, and Faqir of Ipi, among others – many of whom were Amanullah loyalists.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan joined the League of Nations in 1934.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] In the 1930s, the country experienced significant development of roads, infrastructure, the founding of a national bank, and increased education.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Road links in the north played a large part in a growing cotton and textile industry.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The country built close relationships with the Axis powers, with Nazi Germany having the largest share in Afghan development at the time.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Until 1946, King Zahir ruled with the assistance of his uncle, who held the post of prime minister and continued the policies of Nadir Shah.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Another uncle, Shah Mahmud Khan, became prime minister in 1946 and experimented with allowing greater political freedom.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] He was replaced in 1953 by Mohammed Daoud Khan, a Pashtun nationalist who sought the creation of a Pashtunistan, leading to highly tense relations with Pakistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Daoud Khan pressed for social modernization reforms and sought a closer relationship with the Soviet Union.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Afterward, the 1964 constitution was formed, and the first non-royal prime minister was sworn in.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Zahir Shah, like his father Nadir Shah, had a policy of maintaining national independence while pursuing gradual modernization, creating nationalist feeling, and improving relations with the United Kingdom.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan was neither a participant in World War II nor aligned with either power bloc in the Cold War.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] However, it was a beneficiary of the latter rivalry as both the Soviet Union and the United States vied for influence by building Afghanistan's main highways, airports, and other vital infrastructure.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] On a per capita basis, Afghanistan received more Soviet development aid than any other country.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] In 1973, while the King was in Italy, Daoud Khan launched a bloodless coup and became the first president of Afghanistan, abolishing the monarchy.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] In April 1978, the communist People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan (PDPA) seized power in a bloody coup d'état against then-President Mohammed Daoud Khan, in what is called the Saur Revolution.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The PDPA declared the establishment of the Democratic Republic of Afghanistan, with its first leader named as People's Democratic Party General Secretary Nur Muhammad Taraki.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] This would trigger a series of events that would dramatically turn Afghanistan from a peaceful (albeit poor and secluded) country to a hotbed of conflict and terrorism.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The PDPA initiated various social, symbolic, and land distribution reforms that provoked strong opposition, while also brutally oppressing political dissidents.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] This caused unrest and quickly expanded into a state of civil war by 1979, waged by guerrilla *mujahideen* (and smaller Maoist guerrillas) against regime forces countrywide.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] It quickly turned into a proxy war as the Pakistani government provided these rebels with covert training centers, the United States supported them through Pakistan's Inter-Services Intelligence (ISI), and the Soviet Union sent thousands of military advisers to support the PDPA regime.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Meanwhile, there was increasingly hostile friction between the competing factions of the PDPA – the dominant Khalq and the more moderate Parcham.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] In October 1979, PDPA General Secretary Taraki was assassinated in an internal coup orchestrated by then-prime minister Hafizullah Amin, who became the new general secretary of the PDPA.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The situation in the country deteriorated under Amin, and thousands of people went missing.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Displeased with Amin's government, the Soviet Army invaded the country in December 1979, heading for Kabul and killing Amin.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] A Soviet-organized regime, led by Parcham's Babrak Karmal but inclusive of both factions (Parcham and Khalq), filled the vacuum.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Soviet troops in more substantial numbers were deployed to stabilize Afghanistan under Karmal, marking the beginning of the Soviet–Afghan War.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Lasting nine years, the war caused the deaths of between 562,000 and 2 million Afghans, and displaced about 6 million people who subsequently fled Afghanistan, mainly to Pakistan and Iran.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Heavy air bombardment destroyed many countryside villages, millions of landmines were planted, and some cities such as Herat and Kandahar were also damaged from bombardment.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] After the Soviet withdrawal, another civil war ensued until the communist regime under PDPA leader Mohammad Najibullah collapsed in 1992.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Soviet–Afghan War had drastic social effects on Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The militarization of society led to heavily armed police, private bodyguards, openly armed civil defense groups, and the like becoming the norm in Afghanistan for decades thereafter.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The traditional power structure had shifted from the clergy, community elders, intelligentsia, and military in favor of powerful warlords.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Another civil war broke out after the creation of a dysfunctional coalition government between leaders of various *mujahideen* factions.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Amid a state of anarchy and factional infighting, various *mujahideen* factions committed widespread rape, murder, and extortion, while Kabul was heavily bombarded and partially destroyed by the fighting.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Several failed reconciliations and alliances occurred between different leaders.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban emerged in September 1994 as a movement and militia of students (*talib*) from Islamic madrassas (schools) in Pakistan, who soon had military support from Pakistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Taking control of Kandahar city that year, they conquered more territories until finally driving out the government of Rabbani from Kabul in 1996, where they established an emirate.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban were condemned internationally for the harsh enforcement of their interpretation of Islamic sharia law, which resulted in the brutal treatment of many Afghans, especially women.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] During their rule, the Taliban and their allies committed massacres against Afghan civilians, denied UN food supplies to starving civilians, and conducted a policy of scorched earth, burning vast areas of fertile land and destroying tens of thousands of homes.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] After the fall of Kabul to the Taliban, Ahmad Shah Massoud and Abdul Rashid Dostum formed the Northern Alliance, later joined by others, to resist the Taliban.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Dostum's forces were defeated by the Taliban during the Battles of Mazar-i-Sharif in 1997 and 1998; Pakistan's Chief of Army Staff, Pervez Musharraf, began sending thousands of Pakistani militants to help the Taliban defeat the Northern Alliance.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] By 2000, the Northern Alliance only controlled 10% of the territory, cornered in the northeast.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] On 9 September 2001, Massoud was assassinated by two Arab suicide attackers in Panjshir Valley.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Around 400,000 Afghans died in internal conflicts between 1990 and 2001.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] In October 2001, the United States invaded Afghanistan to remove the Taliban from power after they refused to hand over Osama bin Laden, the prime suspect of the September 11 attacks, who was a "guest" of the Taliban and was operating his al-Qaeda network in Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The majority of Afghans supported the American invasion.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] During the initial invasion, US and UK forces bombed al-Qaeda training camps, and later, in cooperation with the Northern Alliance, the Taliban regime came to an end.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] In December 2001, after the Taliban government was overthrown, the Afghan Interim Administration under Hamid Karzai was formed.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The International Security Assistance Force (ISAF) was established by the United Nations Security Council to assist the Karzai administration and provide basic security.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] By this time, after two decades of war as well as an acute famine at the time, Afghanistan had one of the highest infant and child mortality rates in the world, the lowest life expectancy, much of the population suffered from hunger and malnutrition, and infrastructure was in ruins.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Many foreign donors started providing aid and assistance to rebuild the war-torn country.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] As coalition troops entered Afghanistan to help the rebuilding process, the Taliban began an insurgency to regain control.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan remained one of the poorest countries in the world because of a lack of foreign investment, government corruption, and the Taliban insurgency.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Afghan government was able to establish some democratic structures, adopting a constitution in 2004 with the name Islamic Republic of Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Attempts were made, often with the support of foreign donor countries, to improve the country's economy, healthcare, education, transport, and agriculture.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] ISAF forces also began to train the Afghan National Security Forces.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Following 2002, nearly five million Afghans were repatriated.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The number of NATO troops present in Afghanistan peaked at 140,000 in 2011, dropping to approximately 16,000 in 2018.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] In September 2014, Ashraf Ghani became president after the 2014 Afghan presidential election, in which, for the first time in Afghanistan's history, power was democratically transferred.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] On 28 December 2014, NATO formally ended ISAF combat operations and transferred full security responsibility to the Afghan government.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The NATO-led Operation Resolute Support was formed the same day as a successor to ISAF.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Thousands of NATO troops remained in the country to train and advise Afghan government forces and continue their fight against the Taliban.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] A report titled *Body Count* concluded that 106,000–170,000 civilians had been killed as a result of the fighting in Afghanistan at the hands of all parties to the conflict.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] On 19 February 2020, the United States–Taliban deal was made in Qatar.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] NATO Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg announced on 14 April 2021 that the alliance had agreed to start withdrawing its troops from Afghanistan by 1 May.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Soon after NATO troops began withdrawing, the Taliban launched an offensive against the Afghan government and quickly advanced in front of collapsing Afghan government forces.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban captured the capital city of Kabul on 15 August 2021, after regaining control over a vast majority of Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Several foreign diplomats and Afghan government officials, including President Ashraf Ghani, were evacuated from the country, with many Afghan civilians attempting to flee along with them.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] On 17 August, first vice president Amrullah Saleh proclaimed himself caretaker president and announced the formation of an anti-Taliban front with a reported 6,000+ troops in the Panjshir Valley, along with Ahmad Massoud.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] However, by 6 September, the Taliban had taken control of most of Panjshir Province, with resistance fighters retreating to the mountains.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Clashes in the valley ceased in mid-September.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] According to the Costs of War Project, 176,000 people were killed in the conflict, including 46,319 civilians, between 2001 and 2021.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] According to the Uppsala Conflict Data Program, at least 212,191 people were killed in the conflict.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Though the state of war in the country ended in 2021, armed conflict persists in some regions amid fighting between the Taliban and the local branch of the Islamic State, as well as an anti-Taliban Republican insurgency.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban government is led by supreme leader Hibatullah Akhundzada and acting prime minister Hasan Akhund, who took office on 7 September 2021.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Akhund is one of the four founders of the Taliban and was a deputy prime minister of the previous emirate; his appointment was seen as a compromise between moderates and hardliners.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] A new, all-male cabinet was formed, which included Abdul Hakim Haqqani as minister of justice.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] On 20 September 2021, United Nations Secretary-General António Guterres received a letter from acting minister of foreign affairs Amir Khan Muttaqi to formally claim Afghanistan's seat as a member state for their official spokesman in Doha, Suhail Shaheen.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The United Nations did not recognize the previous Taliban government and chose to work with the then government-in-exile instead.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Western nations suspended most of their humanitarian aid to Afghanistan following the Taliban's August 2021 takeover of the country; the World Bank and International Monetary Fund also halted their payments.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] More than half of Afghanistan's 39 million people faced an acute food shortage in October 2021.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Human Rights Watch reported on 11 November 2021 that Afghanistan was facing widespread famine due to an economic and banking crisis.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban initially significantly tackled corruption, improving on the corruption perceptions index from 174th to 150th out of 180 countries from 2021 to 2022, but dropping to 162nd in 2023.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Taliban have also reportedly reduced bribery and extortion in public service areas.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] At the same time, the human rights situation in the country has deteriorated.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Following the 2001 invasion, more than 5.7 million refugees returned to Afghanistan; however, in 2021, 2.6 million Afghans remained refugees, primarily in Iran and Pakistan, and another 4 million were internally displaced.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] In October 2023, the Pakistani government ordered the expulsion of Afghans from Pakistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Iran also decided to deport Afghan nationals back to Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Taliban authorities condemned the deportations of Afghans as an "inhuman act".
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan faced a humanitarian crisis in late 2023.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] On 10 November 2024, Afghanistan's Foreign Ministry confirmed that Taliban representatives would attend the 2024 United Nations Climate Change Conference, marking the first time the country participated since the Taliban's return to power in 2021.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan had been barred from previous summits due to the lack of global recognition of the Taliban regime.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] In May 2025, Iran ordered the mass deportation of an estimated 4 million Afghan migrants and refugees.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The 2025–2026 hunger crisis in Afghanistan is one of the world's most severe, with over 17 million people—one-third of the population—requiring urgent food assistance.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Driven by persistent drought, economic collapse, and massive refugee returns, the crisis has left over 4.9 million children and women needing malnutrition treatment.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan is located in Southern-Central Asia.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The region centered in Afghanistan is considered the "crossroads of Asia", and the country has had the nickname Heart of Asia.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] At over 652,864 km2 (252,072 sq mi), Afghanistan is the world's 41st largest country.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] It is slightly bigger than France and smaller than Myanmar, and about the size of Texas in the United States.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] There is no coastline, as Afghanistan is landlocked.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The geography in Afghanistan is varied, but is mostly mountainous and rugged, with some unusual mountain ridges accompanied by plateaus and river basins.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] It is dominated by the Hindu Kush range, the western extension of the Himalayas that stretches to eastern Tibet via the Pamir Mountains and Karakoram Mountains in Afghanistan's far north-east.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Most of the highest points are in the east, consisting of fertile mountain valleys, often considered part of the "Roof of the World".
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Hindu Kush ends at the west-central highlands, creating plains in the north and southwest, namely the Turkestan Plains and the Sistan Basin; these two regions consist of rolling grasslands and semi-deserts, as well as hot, windy deserts, respectively.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Forests exist in the corridor between the provinces of Nuristan and Paktika (see East Afghan montane conifer forests), and tundra in the northeast.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The country's highest point is Noshaq, at 7,492 m (24,580 ft) above sea level.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The lowest point is located in Jowzjan Province along the Amu River bank, at 258 m (846 ft) above sea level.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Despite having numerous rivers and reservoirs, large parts of the country are dry.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The endorheic Sistan Basin is one of the world's driest regions.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Amu Darya rises in the north of the Hindu Kush, while the nearby Hari River flows west towards Herat, and the Arghandab River flows from the central region southwards.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] To the south and west of the Hindu Kush flow a number of streams that are tributaries of the Indus River, such as the Helmand River.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Kabul River flows in an easterly direction to the Indus, ending at the Indian Ocean.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan receives heavy snow during the winter in the Hindu Kush and Pamir Mountains, and the melting snow in the spring season enters the rivers, lakes, and streams.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] However, two-thirds of the country's water flows into the neighboring countries of Iran, Pakistan, and Turkmenistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] As reported in 2010, the state needs more than US$2 billion to rehabilitate its irrigation systems so that the water is properly managed.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] In Afghanistan, forest cover accounts for approximately 2% of the total land area, equivalent to 1,208,440 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, which remained unchanged since 1990.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Of the naturally regenerating forest, 0% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity), and around 0% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] For the year 2015, 100% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The northeastern Hindu Kush mountain range, located in and around the Badakhshan Province of Afghanistan, is situated in a geologically active area where earthquakes occur almost every year.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] They can be deadly and destructive, causing landslides in some parts or avalanches during the winter.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] In June 2022, a destructive 5.9 earthquake struck near the border with Pakistan, killing at least 1,150 people and sparking fears of a major humanitarian crisis.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] On 7 October 2023, a 6.3 magnitude earthquake struck northwest of Herat, killing over 1,400 people.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The country is generally arid in the summers, with most rainfall falling between December and April.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The lower areas of northern and western Afghanistan are the driest, with precipitation more common in the east.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Although proximate to India, Afghanistan is mostly outside the monsoon zone, except the Nuristan Province, which occasionally receives summer monsoon rain.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Although Afghanistan has contributed minimally to global greenhouse gas emissions, it is one of the most vulnerable countries to climate change and least prepared to cope with its impacts.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Climate change in Afghanistan is causing more frequent and severe droughts.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Severe drought conditions affect 25 of the country's 34 provinces, impacting over half the population.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] These droughts cause desertification, reduce food and water security, disrupt agriculture, and cause internal displacement.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Extreme rainfall over short periods is also more likely, increasing the risk of floods and landslides.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Due to rising temperatures, almost 14% of Afghanistan's glacier coverage was lost between 1990 and 2015, increasing the risk of glacial lake outburst floods.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] By 2050, climate change could displace an additional 5 million people within Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Several types of mammals exist throughout Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Snow leopards and brown bears live in the high elevation alpine tundra regions.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Marco Polo sheep exclusively live in the Wakhan Corridor region of north-east Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Foxes, wolves, otters, deer, wild sheep, lynx and other big cats populate the mountain forest region of the east.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] In the semi-desert northern plains, wildlife include a variety of birds, hedgehogs, gophers, and large carnivores such as jackals and hyenas.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Gazelles, wild pigs and jackals populate the steppe plains of the south and west, while mongoose and cheetahs exist in the semi-desert south.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Marmots and ibex also live in the high mountains of Afghanistan, and pheasants exist in some parts of the country.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The Afghan hound is a native breed of dog known for its fast speed and its long hair; it is relatively known in the west.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Endemic fauna of Afghanistan includes the Afghan flying squirrel, Afghan snowfinch, *Paradactylodon* (or the "Paghman mountain salamander"), *Stigmella kasyi*, *Vulcaniella kabulensis*, Afghan leopard gecko, *Wheeleria parviflorellus*, among others.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan has a wide variety of birds despite its relatively arid climate – an estimated 460 species of which 235 breed within.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The forest region of Afghanistan has vegetation such as pine trees, spruce trees, fir trees and larches, whereas the steppe grassland regions consist of broadleaf trees, short grass, perennial plants and shrublands.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] The colder high elevation regions are composed of hardy grasses and small flowering plants.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Several regions are designated protected areas; there are three national parks: Band-e Amir, Wakhan and Nuristan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p01] Afghanistan had a 2018 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 8.85/10, ranking it 15th globally out of 172 countries.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Following the effective collapse of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan during the 2021 Taliban offensive, the Taliban declared the country an Islamic Emirate.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] A new caretaker government was announced on 7 September.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] As of July 2025, only the Russian Federation has recognized the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan as the *de jure* government of Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In the V-Dem Democracy Indices, Afghanistan ranks amongst the lowest as a "closed autocracy," ranking at 176th and 177th out of 179 countries in electoral democracy and liberal democracy indices respectively.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan operates on a centralised unitary form of government.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] A traditional instrument of governance in Afghanistan is the *loya jirga* (grand assembly), a Pashtun consultative meeting that was mainly organized for choosing a new head of state, adopting a new constitution, or to settle national or regional issue such as war.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Loya jirgas have been held since at least 1747, with the most recent one occurring from June to July 2022.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] President Ashraf Ghani, having fled the country during the Taliban advance to either Tajikistan or Uzbekistan, emerged in the United Arab Emirates and said that he supported such negotiations and was in talks to return to Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Many figures within the Taliban generally agreed that continuation of the 2004 Constitution of Afghanistan may, if correctly applied, be workable as the basis for the new religious state as their objections to the former government were political, and not religious.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Hours after the final flight of American troops left Kabul on 30 August, a Taliban official interviewed said that a new government would likely be announced as early as Friday 3 September after Jumu'ah.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] It was added that Hibatullah Akhundzada would be officially named Emir, with cabinet ministers being revealed at the Arg in an official ceremony.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Abdul Ghani Baradar would be named head of government as Prime Minister, while other important positions would go to Sirajuddin Haqqani and Mullah Yaqoob.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Beneath the supreme leader, day-to-day governance will be entrusted to the cabinet.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In a report by CNN-News18, sources said the new government was going to be governed similarly to Iran with Hibatullah Akhundzada as supreme leader similar to the role of Saayid Ali Khamenei, and would be based out of Kandahar.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Baradar or Yaqoob would be head of government as Prime minister.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The government's ministries and agencies will be under a cabinet presided over by the Prime Minister.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The Supreme Leader would preside over an executive body known as the Supreme Council with anywhere from 11 to 72 members.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Abdul Hakim Haqqani is likely to be promoted to Chief justice.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] According to the report, the new government will take place within the framework of an amended 1964 Constitution of Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Government formation was delayed due to concerns about forming a broad-based government acceptable to the international community.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] It was later added however that the Taliban's Rahbari Shura, the group's leadership council was divided between the hardline Haqqani Network and moderate Abdul Ghani Baradar over appointments needed to form an "inclusive" government.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Reports claimed that this culminated in a skirmish which led to Baradar being injured and treated in Pakistan, however this was denied by Baradar himself.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] As of early September 2021 the Taliban were planning the cabinet to be men-only.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Journalists and other human rights activists, mostly women, protested in Herat and Kabul, calling for women to be included.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The acting Cabinet announced on 7 September was men-only, and the Ministry of Women's Affairs was abolished.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] As of July 2025, only Russia has recognized the Taliban government as the legitimate authorities of Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The U.N has stated that recognition was impossible so long as restrictions on female education and employment remained.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] On 16 September 2024, the Taliban suspended polio vaccination campaigns in Afghanistan, as reported by the United Nations, posing a significant risk to global polio eradication efforts.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In a decree by Hibatullah Akhundzada on 15 August 2025, the description of the government as interim was dropped, with all ministers remaining in their posts, but on a permanent rather than acting basis.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan is administratively divided into 34 provinces (*wilayat*).
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Each province has a governor and a capital.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The country is further divided into nearly 400 provincial districts, each of which normally covers a city or several villages.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Each district is represented by a district governor.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The provincial governors are now appointed by the Prime Minister of Afghanistan, and the district governors are selected by the provincial governors.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The provincial governors are representatives of the central government in Kabul and are responsible for all administrative and formal issues within their provinces.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] There are also provincial councils that are elected through direct and general elections for four years.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The functions of provincial councils are to take part in provincial development planning and to participate in the monitoring and appraisal of other provincial governance institutions.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] According to article 140 of the constitution and the presidential decree on electoral law, mayors of cities should be elected through free and direct elections for a four-year term.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In practice however, mayors are appointed by the government.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan became a member of the United Nations in 1946.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Relations with Pakistan have often been tense for various reasons such as the Durand Line border issue and alleged Pakistani involvement in Afghan insurgent groups.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The present Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan is currently partially recognized, but has had notable unofficial ties with China, Pakistan, and Qatar.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Under the previous Islamic Republic of Afghanistan, it enjoyed cordial relations with a number of NATO and allied nations, particularly the United States, Canada, United Kingdom, Germany, Australia, and Turkey.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In 2012, the United States and the then-republic in Afghanistan signed their Strategic Partnership Agreement in which Afghanistan became a major non-NATO ally.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Such qualification was rescinded by US President Joe Biden in July 2022.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The Armed Forces of the Islamic Emirate of Afghanistan captured a large amount of weapons, hardware, vehicles, aerocrafts, and equipment from the Afghan National Security Forces following the 2021 Taliban offensive and the Fall of Kabul.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The total value of the captured equipment has been estimated at US$83 billion.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Homosexuality is taboo in Afghan society; according to the Penal Code, homosexual intimacy is punished by up to a year in prison.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Under Sharia law offenders can be punished by death.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] However, an ancient tradition involving male homosexual acts between children and older men (typically wealthy warlords or elite people) called *bacha bazi* persists albeit punishable by the death penalty under Taliban law.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Religious minorities such as Sikhs, Hindus, and Christians have reportedly faced persecution.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Since May 2022, all women in Afghanistan have been required by law to wear full-body coverings when in public (either a burqa or an abaya paired with a niqāb, which leaves only the eyes uncovered).
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] First Deputy Leader Sirajuddin Haqqani claimed the decree is only advisory and no form of hijab is compulsory in Afghanistan, though this contradicts the reality.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] It has been speculated that there is a genuine internal policy division over women's rights between hardliners, including leader Hibatullah Akhundzada, and pragmatists, though they publicly present a united front.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Another decree was issued shortly after the first, requiring female TV presenters to cover their faces during broadcasts.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Since the Taliban takeover, suicides among women have become more common, and the country could now be one of the few where the rate of suicide among women surpasses that among men.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In May 2022, the Taliban dissolved Afghanistan's Human Rights Commission along with four other government departments, citing the country's budget deficit.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] ICC member states are obliged to arrest wanted persons if they are on their territory.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan's nominal GDP was $20.1 billion in 2020, or $81 billion by purchasing power parity (PPP).
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Its GDP per capita is $2,459 (PPP) and $611 by nominal.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Despite having $1 trillion or more in mineral deposits, it remains one of the world's least developed countries.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Its economic output per capita is among the lowest of any country as of 2026.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan's rough physical geography and its landlocked status has been cited as reasons why the country has always been among the least developed in the modern era – a factor where progress is also slowed by contemporary conflict and political instability.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The country imports over $7 billion worth of goods but exports only $784 million, mainly fruits and nuts.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The service sector contributed the most to the GDP (55.9%) followed by agriculture (23%) and industry (21.1%).
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Da Afghanistan Bank serves as the central bank of the nation and the Afghani (AFN) is the national currency, with an exchange rate of about 75 Afghanis to 1 US dollar.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] A number of local and foreign banks operate in the country, including the Afghanistan International Bank, New Kabul Bank, Azizi Bank, Pashtany Bank, Standard Chartered Bank, and the First Micro Finance Bank.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In 2010, one of the main drivers for the economic recovery was the return of over 5 million expatriates, who brought with them entrepreneurship and wealth-creating skills as well as much needed funds to start up businesses.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Many Afghans got involved in construction, which was one of the largest industries in the country at the time.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Some of the major national construction projects include the $35 billion New Kabul City next to the capital, the Aino Mena project in Kandahar, and the Ghazi Amanullah Khan Town near Jalalabad.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Similar development projects have also begun in Herat, Mazar-e-Sharif, and other cities.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] An estimated 400,000 people enter the labor market each year.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Several small companies and factories began operating in different parts of the country, which not only provide revenues to the government but also create new jobs.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Improvements to the business environment have resulted in more than $1.5 billion in telecom investment and created more than 100,000 jobs since 2003.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Afghan rugs are becoming popular again, allowing many carpet dealers around the country to hire more workers; in 2016–17 it was the fourth most exported group of items.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan is a member of WTO, SAARC, ECO, and OIC.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In 2018, a majority of imports come from either Iran, China, Pakistan and Kazakhstan, while 84% of exports are to Pakistan and India.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Since the Taliban's takeover of the country in August 2021, the United States has frozen about $9 billion in assets belonging to the Afghan central bank, blocking the Taliban from accessing billions of dollars held in US bank accounts.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The GDP of Afghanistan is estimated to have dropped by 20% following the Taliban return to power.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Following this, after months of free-fall, the Afghan economy began stabilizing, as a result of the Taliban's restrictions on smuggled imports, limits on banking transactions, and UN aid.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In 2023, the Afghan economy began seeing signs of revival.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] This has also been followed by stable exchange rates, low inflation, stable revenue collection, and the rise of trade in exports.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In the third quarter of 2023, the Afghani rose to be the best performing currency in the world, climbing over 9% against the US dollar.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Agricultural production is the backbone of Afghanistan's economy and has traditionally dominated the economy, employing about 40% of the workforce as of 2018.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The country is known for producing pomegranates, grapes, apricots, melons, and several other fresh and dry fruits.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan also became the world's top producer of cannabis in 2010.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In March 2023, however, cannabis production was banned by a decree from Hibatullah Akhundzada.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Saffron, the most expensive spice, grows in Afghanistan, particularly Herat Province.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In recent years, there has been an uptick in saffron production, which authorities and farmers are using to try to replace poppy cultivation.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Between 2012 and 2019, the saffron cultivated and produced in Afghanistan was consecutively ranked the world's best by the International Taste and Quality Institute.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Production hit record high in 2019 (19,469 kg of saffron), and one kilogram is sold domestically between $634 and $1147.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The availability of cheap diesel-powered water pumps imported from China and Pakistan, and in the 2010s, of cheap solar power to pump water, resulted in expansion of agriculture and population in the southwestern deserts of Afghanistan in Kandahar, Helmand and Nimruz provinces in the 2010s.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Wells have gradually been deepened, but water resources are limited.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Opium is the major crop, but as of 2022, was under attack by the new Taliban government which, to suppress opium production, was systematically suppressing water pumping.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In a 2023 report, poppy cultivation in southern Afghanistan was reduced by over 80% as a result of Taliban campaigns to stop its use toward opium.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] This included a 99% reduction of opium growth in the Helmand Province.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In November 2023, a U.N report showed that in the entirety of Afghanistan, poppy cultivation dropped by over 95%, removing it from its place as being the world's largest opium producer.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The country's natural resources include: coal, copper, iron ore, lithium, uranium, rare earth elements, chromite, gold, zinc, talc, barite, sulfur, lead, marble, precious and semi-precious stones, natural gas, and petroleum.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In 2010, US and Afghan government officials estimated that untapped mineral deposits located in 2007 by the US Geological Survey are worth at least $1 trillion.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] O'Hanlon of the Brookings Institution estimated that if Afghanistan generates about $10 billion per year from its mineral deposits, its gross national product would double and provide long-term funding for critical needs.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The United States Geological Survey (USGS) estimated in 2006 that northern Afghanistan has an average 460 million m3 (2.9 billion bbl) of crude oil, 440 billion m3 (15.7 trillion cu ft) of natural gas, and 67 billion L (562 million US bbl) of natural gas liquids.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In 2011, Afghanistan signed an oil exploration contract with China National Petroleum Corporation (CNPC) for the development of three oil fields along the Amu Darya river in the north.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The country has significant amounts of lithium, copper, gold, coal, iron ore, and other minerals.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The Khanashin carbonatite in Helmand Province contains 1,000,000 tonnes (980,000 long tons; 1,100,000 short tons) of rare earth elements.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In 2007, a 30-year lease was granted for the Aynak copper mine to the China Metallurgical Group for $3 billion, making it the biggest foreign investment and private business venture in Afghanistan's history.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The state-run Steel Authority of India won the mining rights to develop the huge Hajigak iron ore deposit in central Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Government officials estimate that 30% of the country's untapped mineral deposits are worth at least $1 trillion.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] One official asserted that "this will become the backbone of the Afghan economy" and a Pentagon memo stated that Afghanistan could become the "Saudi Arabia of lithium".
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The lithium reserves of 21 Mio. tons could amount to the ones of Bolivia, which is currently viewed as the country with the largest lithium reserves.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Other larger deposits are the ones of bauxite and cobalt.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Access to biocapacity in Afghanistan is lower than world average.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In 2016, Afghanistan had 0.43 global hectares of biocapacity per person within its territory, much less than the world average of 1.6 global hectares per person.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In 2016 Afghanistan used 0.73 global hectares of biocapacity per person—their ecological footprint of consumption.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] This means they use just under double as much biocapacity as Afghanistan contains.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] As a result, Afghanistan is running a biocapacity deficit.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In September 2023, the Taliban signed mining contracts worth $6.5 billion, with extractions based on gold, iron, lead, and zinc in the provinces of Herat, Ghor, Logar, and Takhar.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] According to the World Bank, 98% of the rural population have access to electricity in 2018, up from 28% in 2008.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] As of 2016, Afghanistan produces 1,400 megawatts of power, but still imports the majority of electricity via transmission lines from Iran and the Central Asian states.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The majority of electricity production is via hydropower, helped by the amount of rivers and streams that flow from the mountains.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] However electricity is not always reliable and blackouts happen, including in Kabul.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In recent years an increasing number of solar, biomass and wind power plants have been constructed.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Currently under development are the CASA-1000 project which will transmit electricity from Kyrgyzstan and Tajikistan, and the Turkmenistan-Afghanistan-Pakistan-India (TAPI) gas pipeline.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Power is managed by the Da Afghanistan Breshna Sherkat (DABS, Afghanistan Electricity Company).
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Important dams include the Kajaki Dam, Dahla Dam, and the Sardeh Band Dam.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Tourism is a small industry in Afghanistan due to security issues.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Nevertheless, some 20,000 foreign tourists visit the country annually as of 2016.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In particular an important region for domestic and international tourism is the picturesque Bamyan Valley, which includes lakes, canyons and historical sites, helped by the fact it is in a safe area away from insurgent activity.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Smaller numbers visit and trek in regions such as the Wakhan Valley, which is also one of the world's most remote communities.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] From the late 1960s onwards, Afghanistan was a popular stop on the famous hippie trail, attracting many Europeans and Americans.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Coming from Iran, the trail traveled through various Afghan provinces and cities including Herat, Kandahar and Kabul before crossing to northern Pakistan, northern India, and Nepal.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Tourism peaked in 1977, the year before the start of political instability and armed conflict.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The city of Ghazni has significant history and historical sites, and together with Bamyan city have in recent years been voted Islamic Cultural Capital and South Asia Cultural Capital respectively.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The cities of Herat, Kandahar, Balkh, and Zaranj are also very historic.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The Minaret of Jam in the Hari River valley is a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] A cloak reputedly worn by Islam's prophet Muhammad is kept in the Shrine of the Cloak in Kandahar, a city founded by Alexander the Great and the first capital of Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The citadel of Alexander in the western city of Herat has been renovated in recent years and is a popular attraction.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In the north of the country is the Shrine of Ali, believed by many to be the location where Ali was buried.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The National Museum of Afghanistan in Kabul hosts a large number of Buddhist, Bactrian Greek and early Islamic antiquities; the museum suffered greatly by civil war but has been slowly restoring since the early 2000s.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Unexpectedly, tourism has seen improvement in Afghanistan following the Taliban takeover.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Active efforts by the Taliban encouraged tourism to increase from 691 tourists in 2021, to 2,300 in 2022, to 5,200 in 2023, with some estimates of between 7,000 and 10,000.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] This is, however, threatened by the Islamic State – Khorasan Province, who took responsibility for attacks on tourists, such as the 2024 Bamyan shooting.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Telecommunication services in Afghanistan are provided by Afghan Telecom, Afghan Wireless, Etisalat, MTN Group, and Roshan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The country uses its own space satellite called Afghansat 1, which provides services to millions of phone, internet, and television subscribers.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] By 2001 following years of civil war, telecommunications was virtually a non-existent sector, but by 2016 it had grown to a $2 billion industry, with 22 million mobile phone subscribers and 5 million internet users.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The sector employs at least 120,000 people nationwide.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Due to Afghanistan's geography, transport between various parts of the country has historically been difficult.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The Ring Road is crucially important for domestic and international trade and the economy.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] A key portion of the Ring Road is the Salang Tunnel, completed in 1964, which facilitates travel through the Hindu Kush mountain range and connects northern and southern Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] It is the only land route that connects Central Asia to the Indian subcontinent.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Several mountain passes allow travel between the Hindu Kush in other areas.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Serious traffic accidents are common on Afghan roads and highways, particularly on the Kabul–Kandahar and the Kabul–Jalalabad Road.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Traveling by bus in Afghanistan remains dangerous due to militant activities.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Air transport in Afghanistan is provided by the national carrier, Ariana Afghan Airlines, and by the private company Kam Air.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Airlines from a number of countries also provide flights in and out of the country.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] These include Air India, Emirates, Gulf Air, Iran Aseman Airlines, Pakistan International Airlines, and Turkish Airlines.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The country has four international airports: Kabul International Airport (formerly Hamid Karzai International Airport), Kandahar International Airport, Herat International Airport, and Mazar-e Sharif International Airport.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Including domestic airports, there are 43.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Bagram Air Base is a major military airfield.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] These lines are used for freight only and there is no passenger service.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] A rail line between Khaf, Iran and Herat, western Afghanistan, intended for both freight and passengers, was under construction as of 2019.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] About 125 kilometres (78 mi) of the line will lie on the Afghan side.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Private vehicle ownership has increased substantially since the early 2000s.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Taxis are yellow and consist of both cars and auto rickshaws.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In rural Afghanistan, villagers often use donkeys, mules or horses to transport or carry goods.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Camels are primarily used by the Kochi nomads.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Bicycles are popular throughout Afghanistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The population of Afghanistan was estimated at 35.7 million as of 2024 by the Afghanistan National Statistics and Information Authority, whereas the UN estimates over 42.0 million.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In 1979 the total population was reported to be about 15.5 million.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] About 25.3% are urbanite, 70.4% live in rural areas, and the remaining 4.3% are nomadic.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] An additional 3 million or so Afghans are temporarily housed in neighboring Pakistan and Iran, most of whom were born and raised in those two countries.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] As of 2013, Afghanistan was the largest refugee-producing country in the world, a title held for 32 years.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The current population growth rate is 2.37%, one of the highest in the world outside of Africa.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] This population is expected to reach 82 million by 2050 if current population trends continue.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The population of Afghanistan increased steadily until the 1980s, when civil war caused millions to flee to other countries such as Pakistan.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Millions have since returned and the war conditions contribute to the country having the highest fertility rate outside Africa.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan's healthcare has recovered since the turn of the century, causing falls in infant mortality and increases in life expectancy, although it has the lowest life expectance of any country outside Africa.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] This (along with other factors such as returning refugees) caused rapid population growth in the 2000s that has only recently started to slow down.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Afghanistan 2024 total fertility rate has been estimated at 4.4.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] In 2022 it was 4.5, about twice the world average rate.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The rate has fallen since the early 1980s.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] As estimated by the CIA World Factbook, 26% of the population was urbanized as of 2020.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] This is one of the lowest figures in the world; in Asia it is only higher than Cambodia, Nepal and Sri Lanka.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Urbanization has increased rapidly, particularly in the capital Kabul, due to returning refugees from Pakistan and Iran after 2001, internally displaced people, and rural migrants.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Urbanization in Afghanistan is different from typical urbanization in that it is centered on just a few cities.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Kabul is the largest city, with a population of 5 million.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The other large cities are located generally in the "ring" around the Central Highlands, namely Kandahar in the south, Herat in the west, Mazar-i-Sharif, Kunduz in the north, and Jalalabad in the east.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Afghans are divided into several ethnolinguistic groups.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] According to research data by several institutions in 2019, the Pashtuns are the largest ethnic group, comprising 42%, followed by Tajiks, comprising 27% of the country's population.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The other two major ethnic groups are the Hazaras and Uzbeks, each at 9%.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] A further 10 other ethnic groups are recognized and each are represented in the Afghan National Anthem.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Dari and Pashto are the official languages of Afghanistan; bilingualism is very common.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Dari, which is also referred to as Eastern Persian as it is a variety of and mutually intelligible with Persian (and very often called 'Farsi' by some Afghans like in Iran), functions as the lingua franca in Kabul as well as in much of the northern and northwestern parts of the country.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Native speakers of Dari, of any ethnicity, are sometimes called Farsiwans.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Pashto is the native tongue of the Pashtuns, although many of them are also fluent in Dari while some non-Pashtuns are fluent in Pashto.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Despite the Pashtuns having been dominant in Afghan politics for centuries, Dari remained the preferred language for government and bureaucracy.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] According to CIA World Factbook, Dari Persian is spoken by 78% (L1 + L2) and functions as the lingua franca, while Pashto is spoken by 50%, Uzbek 10%, English 5%, Turkmen 2%, Urdu 2%, Pashayi 1%, Nuristani 1%, Arabic 1%, and Balochi 1% (2021 est).
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Data represent the most widely spoken languages; shares sum to more than 100% because there is much bilingualism in the country and because respondents were allowed to select more than one language.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] There are a number of smaller regional languages, including Uzbek, Turkmen, Balochi, Pashayi, and Nuristani.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] When it comes to foreign languages among the populace, many are able to speak or understand Hindustani (Urdu-Hindi), partly due to returning Afghan refugees from Pakistan and the popularity of Bollywood films respectively.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] English is also understood by some of the population, and has been gaining popularity as of the 2000s.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Some Afghans retain some ability in Russian, which was taught in public schools during the 1980s.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] The CIA estimated in 2009 that 99.7% of the Afghan population was Muslim and most are thought to adhere to the Sunni Hanafi school.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] According to Pew Research Center, as much as 90% are of the Sunni denomination, 7% Shia and 3% non-denominational.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Conversion away from Islam is persecuted, limiting religious freedom.
[src:bachelor-of-science/afghanistan-p02] Afghan Sikhs and Hindus are also found in certain major cities (namely Kabul, Jalalabad, Ghazni, Kandahar) accompanied by gurdwaras and mandirs.
